<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government Expanded with Six Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The 11-day-old ministry led by
Prime Minister I.K. Gujral was expanded today with the induction
of six ministers, including former finance minister P.
Chidambaram, Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
Of the six ministers sworn in here today by Indian President
Shanker Dayal Sharma, four are from the Tamil Maanila Congress
(TMC), a major constituent of the ruling United Front.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil Nadu-based regional party, which had earlier refused
to joint the Gujral government, on Tuesday decided to rejoin the
government to make it more stable.
</P>
<P>
The other two ministers are from the Janata Dal.
</P>
<P>
Among the newly-inducted ministers, P. Chidambaram, M.
Arunachalam, S. Jaipal Reddy were sworn in as cabinet ministers
while Dhanushkodi Athithan, Maqbool Dar and S.R. Balasubramanian
were ministers of state.
</P>
<P>
Only Reddy was a new face while the rest had served in the H.D.
Deve Gowda government.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, except for Reddy, are widely expected to get
back the portfolios they held in the Deve Gowda government.
</P>
<P>
With today's expansion, the strength of the Gujral government
has gone up to 40, of which 19 are of cabinet rank and the rest
ministers of state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
