<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Russia-U.S. Talks, Rifts Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the United States today
reported progress in talks between Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and his United States counterpart, Madeleine
Albright, but said differences remained.
</P>
<P>
The talks focused on a document governing Russian-North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) relations, European security
and relations between Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We have somewhat narrowed the differences," Albright told a
joint news conference with Primakov. She added however that there
was still "some way to go."
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the talks were successful and will be continued.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that the differences between the two sides lay in the
military field.
</P>
<P>
"There are some outstanding issues ... they include mainly
military questions."
</P>
<P>
Russia is trying to strike a deal with NATO so that Moscow will
have a say in NATO's policy-making process after the planned
eastward enlargement of the military bloc.
</P>
<P>
During her last visit to Moscow in February, Albright and
Primakov reached an understanding in principle that a possible
agreement between Russia and NATO should be of legally-binding
nature.
</P>
<P>
Before today's talks, Russian President Boris Yeltsin talked
with Albright by telephone.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the document on Russian-NATO relations must be
prepared with due attention.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the understanding reached in the
Russian-U.S. Helsinki summit must be materialized.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the U.S. government was committed to constructive
dialogue with Russia and sought to find a solution acceptable to
both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
