<HEADLINE> US Personal Incomes, Spending Up in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Personal incomes in the U.S.
increased by 0.6 percent in March, helping to support the second
straight 0.5 percent increase in consumer spending, the Commerce
Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that personal incomes totaled 6.75 trillion
dollars at a seasonally adjusted annual rate in the month, up from
6.71 trillion dollars in February.
</P>
<P>
The 0.6 percent growth in incomes slowed from the revised 0.8
percent gain in the previous month but surpassed the 0.3 percent
increase in January. The February advance originally was reported
to be 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Private wages and salaries, the most closely watched component
of income, rose 27.7 billion dollars on top of a 48.7 billion gain
in February. It was attributed to an increase in employment and
average hourly earnings, which more than offset a decline in
average weekly hours.
</P>
<P>
Disposable income -- income after taxes -- increased by 0.6
percent after surging 0.8 percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumer spending totaled at an annual rate of 5.37
trillion dollars, compared with 5.35 trillion a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The 0.5 percent gain in spending was stronger than the 0.3
percent increase in February but down from the robust 1.2 percent
jump in January.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending, which represents about two-thirds of the
U.S. economy, was the driving force of the economic growth in the
first quarter when it surged at 5.6 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
However, recent data suggest growth is beginning to slow to a
more sustainable pace resulting from the raising of short-term
interest rates in March by the U.S. Federal Reserve in an attempt
to keep the economy from overheating and sparking an acceleration
in inflation.
</P>
<P>
The combination of incomes and spending meant that Americans'
saving rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income --
edged up to 5.3 percent from February's 5.2 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
The personal income and spending figures were not adjusted for
inflation. When adjusted, disposable incomes rose 0.5 percent, the
same as in February. Spending rose 0.4 percent, twice the 0.2
percent gain a month earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
