<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending Down Slightly in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. construction spending in
March declined slightly from the previous month but several
construction sectors remained strong, U.S. Commerce Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that total construction spending reached a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 600.1 billion U.S. dollars in
March, down by 0.2 percent from the revised construction spending
in February.
</P>
<P>
The spending on private construction declined by 0.6 percent to
its lowest level since July 1996, the second straight month of
falling.
</P>
<P>
But spending for the construction of residential buildings
reached a record level in the month. The seasonally adjusted
annual rate jumped by 1 percent to 256.6 billion dollars from
revised February levels.
</P>
<P>
Included in this increase was a boom in spending for
single-family houses that increased the annual spending rate to a
record 159.2 billion dollars. However, total spending rates for
multi-family structures saw a slight dip.
</P>
<P>
Construction spending on projects for hotels, motels and
religious buildings also climbed to record annual spending rates,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Public construction spending jumped 0.9 percent from February's
rate to a record high level, as more dollars were spent into
such projects as schools, water supply facilities and conservation
projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
