<HEADLINE> Mobutu, Kabila Due to Meet on Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Zairean President Mobutu Sese
Seko and rebel leader Laurent Kabila will have their first
face-to-face peace talks on Friday aboard the South African naval
vessel the SAS Outeniqua, presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana
confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
According to Mankahlana, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki would
leave for Luanda, Angola, tonight where he was scheduled to meet
Kabila. He would accompany the rebel leader, whose forces were in
control of more than half of Zaire, to the SAS Outeniqua on
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The South African naval supply ship would be berthed at the
Congolese port city Pointe-Noire, before heading to international
waters where the direct talks are expected to take place.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela, who is expected to
chair the meeting, would leave South Africa on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
He would be met at Pointe-Noire by his Congolese counterpart
Pascal Lissouba and the two leaders would hold talks with Mobutu,
before proceeding to the SAS Outeniqua, Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
A Department of Foreign Affairs statement said Mbeki and
Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad left South Africa this
afternoon to prepare for Friday's meeting between Mobutu and
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The talks would be presided over by Mandela and would also be
attended by Mahomed Sahnoun, the United Nations special envoy to
the Great Lakes region, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
