<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Protest at Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Several hundreds of Palestinians
held a demonstration today at the controversial building site of
Har Homa, a new Jewish neighborhood on the southeastern outskirts
of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Despite condemnation by the Palestinians and the international
community, the construction at Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim), which
started in March, has been continuing under heavy security guard.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrators at today's protest called on Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat to hold a
referendum to determine whether the Palestinian people should
continue the peace process with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian Council Member Salah Tamari, who also
participated in the protest, urged Arafat to "seriously consider
stopping the peace process" if Israel does not stop the Har Homa
building project.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has suspended political contacts and security
cooperation with Israel since the Israeli government decided to
go ahead with the building of Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
A recent Palestinian poll, conducted by the Nablus-based
Palestinian Center for Research and Studies, showed a sharp drop
in support for the peace process from 73 percent to 60 percent
during the past month.
</P>
<P>
This was accompanied by an increase in support for suicide
bombings, with 44 percent of Palestinians from the Gaza Strip
supporting the Tel-Aviv bombing attack in March, compared with 17
percent support for attacks in February-March last year.
</P>
<P>
Support for Hamas, or the Islamic resistance movement, jumped
from 7 percent to 11 percent in Gaza in one month, while the
support for the Oslo accords dropped from 81 percent to 60
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
