<HEADLINE> UK Manufacturing Continues to Grow in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain's manufacturing activity grew
for the 11th consecutive month in April, a leading business survey
showed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The purchasing managers' index published today by the Chartered
Institute of Purchasing and Supply rose to a seasonally-adjusted
53.1 last month from 52.8 in March on the index where figures over
50 indicate growth while below 50 show contraction.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that companies continued to raise output to
meet further improvements in order books although the rate of
growth for export orders again dropped due to the sustained
strength of sterling last month.
</P>
<P>
However, there was little sign of inflationary pressure in the
sector as the prices index was unchanged at 40.5.
</P>
<P>
Britain's economy is in a fairly healthy state, with steady
growth, falling unemployment and low inflation, the institute
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Voting is still underway in the country's general election, but
despite the booming economy, voters seem unlikely to give the
Conservative government any credit as all opinion polls indicated
a big victory for the opposition Labor Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
