<HEADLINE> S. African Cabinet Calls for Anti-Mercenary Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africans invloved in
mercenary activity outside the country are to serve 10 years in
jail or pay a fine of up to one million Rands (227,272 U.S.
dollars), Southern African Broadcasting Association (SABA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The South African cabinet, which approved the bill yesterday,
would introduce legislation in parliament, proposing such a
severe punishment and barring illegal mercenary activity abroad,
SABA said.
</P>
<P>
Companies and individuals, who want to offer any
military-related sevices outside South Africa, will in future
have to seek government approval before signing contracts,
National Conventional Arms Control Committee Chairman Kader Asmal
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asmal, also Minister of Water Affairs and Forestry, said he
would also request other countries to implement similar laws.
</P>
<P>
The South African government has been embarrassed at reports
of South African mercenary activity abroad.
</P>
<P>
The best known mercenary recruiting outfit is Pretoria-based
Executive Outcomes, which reportedly deployed its soldiers in
Angola and Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
