<HEADLINE> BMW Chief Warns Against British Opting out of EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Bernd Pischetsrieder, head of the
German leading car manufacturer BMW, has warned that Britain could
lose its role as Europe's main financial center if it stays out of
a single European currency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC radio interview today, Pischetsrieder warned
that British manufacturing would be harmed if the country did not
take part in European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt would take over from London as the leading financial
center in Europe, he said. "If Britain should stay out for a long
time at the beginning, I think the financial capital of Europe
will be Frankfurt, not London anymore."
</P>
<P>
Pischetsrieder, whose company owns some shares of British car
maker Rover, stressed that remaining outside a single currency
zone would also hurt British manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
"This is very easily described. BMW will earn more money by
exporting more BMWs to Britain, and Rover will increase its losses
because they are already selling more than 50 percent outside
Britain, which means Britain will be less competitive."
</P>
<P>
"You can't increase local selling prices, so Rover is
accumulating higher losses, and so is everybody else manufacturing
in Britain," he said. 
</P>
