<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Wheat Production to Be 5m Tons Lower for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Following the revisions for several
countries, world wheat production is now forecast 5 m. tons lower
at 578 m. tons, compared with 580 m. in 1996, International Grains
Council (IGC) announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The main changes include lower figures for the EC and United
States, and increases for China and Central/Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Although small adjustments also have been made to forecast
import requirements for some countries, the projection for world
wheat trade remains at 94 m. tons, 3 m. up on 1996/97, IGC said.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast at 581 m. tons, down 1 m.
tons, and world stocks are projected to fall by 3 m. tons. during
1997/98 to 95 m. tons, it added.
</P>
<P>
As far as coarse grains is concerned, world production is
forecast at a record 897 m. tons, compared with 889 m. tons in
1996, according to IGC's announcement.
</P>
<P>
Better prospects for Central/Eastern Europe, Russia, Ukraine,
the United States and some African countries may be only partly
offset by reductions in output in the EC, Canada and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade in coarse grains will again depend heavily
on developments in Far East Asia, which accounts for around half
of global imports, IGC said.
</P>
<P>
The growth of some 5 percent in annual output of compound feed
in recent years, dominated by demand for pig and poultry rations,
should lead to a further expansion in demand for maize, in
particular, IGC argued.
</P>
<P>
World trade in all coarse grains is projected at 90 m. tons, up
from 88 m. tons this season, it estimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
