<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-01 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Al-Assad Call for Furthering Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Syrian President Hafez Al-Assad today underlined the need for
pushing forward the deadlocked Mideast peace process but ruled out
an imminent pan-Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference held at the end of the meeting in
the Red Sea resort of Sharm el Sheikh, the two presidents
asserted their firm commitment to comprehensive and just peace on
the basis of restoring Arab rights and the land-for-peace
principle.
</P>
<P>
They cautioned that the peace process is going through a state
of stalemate, which should be overcome through "every possible
effort."
</P>
<P>
"Both the Arabs and Israelis want peace," Mubarak said, adding
that just and comprehensive peace has to precede cooperation in
the Mideast region.
</P>
<P>
Hailing Egypt and Syria as the "prop of the Arab nation,"
Al-Assad asserted their keenness on standing up to the current
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Al-Assad noted that "we want peace but it has to be
based on restoring our rights."
</P>
<P>
"We have a long way to go but we must go on," he added.
</P>
<P>
During the two-hour talks, the presidents continued their
frequent discussions on the need to achieve a just, comprehensive
and durable peace in the region, as well as to close Arab ranks.
</P>
<P>
"Arab-Arab relations are as staunch as they were and contacts
between the Arab leaders are sustained," Mubarak said in reply to
a question if inter-Arab relations are better than they were
before the Arab summit held in Cairo last June.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak opposed holding an imminent Arab summit and stressed
the importance of implementing resolutions of the Cairo Summit
that recommend reconsidering normalization steps with Israel if it
fails to comply with signed peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
But in case the peace process runs into a dead end, he said,
Arabs will hold such a summit to make resolute decisions. "But I
wish it never happens," added Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Syria had favored a comprehensive Arab summit to confront the
Israeli settlement practice, but Egypt said such a move is still
premature.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Al-Assad deplored that there are "some parties in
the region that would not propel peace process."
</P>
<P>
The Syrian president, accompanied by Vice President Abdul Halim
Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouq Al-Shara, flew to the southern
tip of the Sinai peninsula this morning on a lightning visit to
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The meeting topped Mubarak's renewed diplomatic offensive to
revive the stalled peace effort as the Arabs become increasingly
disillusioned with what they perceived as a biased U.S. mediation
role in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
Returning from his brief visit to Kuwait and Saudi Arabia last
weekend, Mubarak said he is ready to organize a mini Arab summit
grouping Jordan's King Hussein, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and Al-Assad but he made this conditional on Israel's readiness to
take steps to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also offered to host a four-way summit grouping
Israel's Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, Arafat and King Hussein, on
the condition that Israel halts settlement buildings on Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with the
Jewish state, has been a mediator in the peace process which
witnesses stalemates in all tracks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
