<HEADLINE> Joint Investigative Mission for Eastern Zaire Meets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The three members of the
Joint Investigative mission into human rights violations in
eastern Zaire have started their two days of preparatory meetings
in Geneva before traveling to the region on Saturday, a U.N.
spokesman announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press briefing that the Mission
would be briefed by United Nations agencies and non-governmental
organizations and would elaborate the terms of reference for the
Mission and its work-plan.
</P>
<P>
The mission will also hear the views of representatives of the
Zairian government and the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of Congo/Zaire (ADFL).
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council, in a presidential statement adopted
on Wednesday, expressed once again its deep concern over
continuing reports of massacres, other atrocities and violations
of international humanitarian law in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The Zairian rebels have reportedly taken control of the eastern
half of Zaire in a seven-month campaign to oust President Mobutu
Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council statement underlined the importance of
the Mission, reiterating its call on the ADFL and others in the
region to cooperate with the Mission by ensuring unimpeded
access to all areas and sites under investigation, as well as
the security of the members.
</P>
<P>
The Mission was established by resolution 1997/58 of the
United Nations Commission on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
In opening comments to the meeting in Geneva earlier in the
day, the Officer-in-Charge of the High Commissioner/Center for
Human Rights, Ralph Zacklin, said that the Mission had been
described as a "litmus test of the good faith and willingness of
all parties to cooperate with the United Nations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
