<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel leader Laurent-Desire
Kabila said here today the march on Kinshasa will continue
despite the pending meeting with ailing President Mubutu Sese
Seko.
</P>
<P>
Briefing local journalists after a meeting with Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe at state house in Harare, Kabila said,
"why not? I think we must go forward. We must liberate Kinshasa
but we are now discussing with others to try and solve the
problem by peaceful means."
</P>
<P>
Initial reports said the meeting between the two protagonists
was scheduled to take place on Friday on a South African naval
supply ship.
</P>
<P>
"I have been told it (meeting) will now be on Saturday because
Mobutu has changed his mind again," said Kabila, sporting his
trademark green safari suit.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which the rebel leader said would discuss a
peaceful transfer of power, if held, would be the first
face-to-face between Mobutu and Kabila, whose rebels have seized
more than half of Zaire since October and are advancing on the
capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who arrived here today from his south eastern Zaire
headquarters, said he had come to Zimbabwe to brief Mugabe in his
capacity as the incoming Organisation of African Unity (OAU)
chairman on developments in his country and to seek the southern
African nation's support for their struggle.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who said he had not received an invitation to the
meeting which will be chaired by South African president Nelson
Mandale, said he hoped the two would agree "on the way forward"
for the sake of peace and stability in the region and Africa as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe added, "my own attitude is to wish them well and hope
this meeting will produce some understanding that will lead the
people of Zaire to new peace."
</P>
<P>
Kabila was due to leave Harare immediately after the meeting.
</P>
