<HEADLINE> International Organization for Migration Praises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Geneva-based
International Organization for Migration (IOM) James Pourcell
praised Angola here today for its resettlement of ex-servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Pourcell told reporters at the end of his four-day visit to
Angola that about 65,200 ex-servicemen and their families have so
far been resettled and given relief materials in the southern
African country.
</P>
<P>
However, the pace of demobilizing and resettling fighters of
the former warring parties is slow, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the large-scale demobilization, for which the IOM
needs 28 million U.S. Dollars, may be completed in five months.
</P>
<P>
The IOM will manage to have 100,000 Angolan military
personnel return to the civil life with the support of
10 non-governmental groups engaged in humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
He said he will visit some donor countries in the near future
in a bid to acquire money.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the visit of Pourcell, who arrived here on April
28, is to raise funds for Angola's demobilization. He will leave
here for Geneva later today.
</P>
<P>
The 55-member IOM, set up in the 1950s, aims to ensure the
worldwide migrants to move orderly. enditem

