<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Consumers Think Now Is Good Time to Buy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 1 (Xinhua) -- More Canadian consumers think that
now is a good time to make a major purchase, though many of them
felt their financial situation had worsened over the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
Releasing today its Spring 1997 Index of Consumer Attitudes,
the Conference Board of Canada said the index reached 106.9, up
2.1 points over the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
"Low interest rates and the belief that rates have hit bottom
have convinced consumers that now is a good time to buy," said
Paul Darby, director of the economic services of the board, a
renowned private economic think-tank here.
</P>
<P>
Canadian interest rates have been at its bottom for the time
being, with the prime lending rate at 4.75 at the end of March, a
level not seen in over 40 years.
</P>
<P>
The current low rates, combined with the belief that the rates
will not go any lower, have convinced 56.8 percent of respondents
that now is a good time to make a major purchase.
</P>
<P>
However, "labour market weakness continues to hold back further
growth in our consumer index," Darby said.
</P>
<P>
"Consumer balance sheets are still fragile thanks to low real
disposable income growth and historically low interest rates which
are making people want to borrow. The result is high consumer and
mortgage debt levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the board Index of Business Confidence
continues to set records, up 7.1 points to a level of 160.3.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders feel current investment conditions are
excellent and they expect their financial situations to improve.
</P>
<P>
"Canadian businesses feel that economic conditions will improve
over the next six months," Darby added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
