<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Report: Half of World Population be Urban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Half of the world population
will be urban dwellers by 2006 although the population
urbanization is developing at a slower pace than previously
envisioned, the United Nations Public Information Department said
today.
</P>
<P>
The department quoted a recently released 1996 Revision of
World Urbanization Prospects as saying that some 46 percent of the
world population are now urban dwellers, but the percentage is
expected to raise to half of the population by 2006.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. study, over three fifths of the world
population will be urban by 2030, five years later than previously
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo is currently the largest urban agglomeration in the
world, with 27.2 million residents in 1996--more than one and a
half times as large as the world's second largest agglomeration,
Mexico City, with 16.9 million.
</P>
<P>
The Revision updates estimates and projections of urban,
rural and city populations. These figures, which are the standard
and consistent set used by the United Nations systems and
international community, are updated every two years by the
population service.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. figures show that the urban growth rate in the less
developed regions reached 3.4 percent per annum during 1990-1995,
compared with only 0.7 percent in the more developed regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
