<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Surgeons Seal Hole in Heart of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Surgeons at the University of Nigeria
Teaching Hospital in Enugu State have successfully sealed a hole
in the heart of a two-year-old boy, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The operation, lasting more than two hours, was performed last
week by a team of doctors led by Martin Aghaji, a consultant
cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
The boy's mother, whose name was not identified, expressed her
joy at the outcome of the surgery, saying that her son's heart
problem was noticed when he was six months old.
</P>
<P>
A hole in the heart will lead to blood flowing from the left side
of the heart to the right rather than the other way round, medical
experts say.
</P>
<P>
The wrong circulation of blood, they say, leaves too much
blood in the heart, thus resulting in too much pressure being
exerted on it, a situation which could lead to the collapse of
the heart.
</P>
<P>
The mother said she once had planned to have the operation
abroad, which would have cost the family two million Naira (about
24,000 U.S. Dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
