<HEADLINE> Ex-US Senator to Advise on Gulf War Illnesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen
today appointed former Senator Warren B. Rudman as a special
adviser on Gulf War illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made one day after a White House panel
reported to the president that the military investigation into
whether U.S. troops may have been exposed to chemical weapons
during the Gulf War is moving too slowly.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news briefing with visiting Ukrainian
Defense Minister Olexander Kuzmuk, Cohen today told reporters that
Rudman would serve as an "independent overseer" of the collection
of facts.
</P>
<P>
Rudman, who left the Senate in 1992, now serves as vice
chairman of President Bill Clinton's Foreign Intelligence Advisory
Board.
</P>
<P>
"There still continues to be criticism about the level of
cooperation that is existing. There is some criticism directed at
the department," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Rudman will ensure that "the information is not
being withheld, there is no cover-up."
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Advisory Committee on Gulf Illnesses said in a
report to the White House Wednesday that Pentagon was too cautious
in drawing conclusions about which troops could have been exposed
to Iraqi chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Although experts are divided over whether exposure to chemical
weapons can cause the kinds of health effects Gulf War veterans
have reported, the panel said troops should have been notified of
any potential exposure to poisons. 
</P>
