<P>
Hamdoun also expressed the hope that the UNSCOM would stop
"issuing political comments and statements and keep committing
to its assigned technical and professional aspects."
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation is the only active way to get closed all
files on Iraq's mass destruction weapons and consequently to get
para 22 of the U.N. resolution 687 implemented, Hamdoun
stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to para 22 of the cease-fire resolution 687 issued
at the end of the 1991 Gulf War, sanctions imposed on Iraq will
be lifted after Iraq fulfills all its commitments to the
U.N. relevant resolutions concerning Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Hamdoun informed Annan of Iraq's annoyance for the slow
implementation of the oil-for-food deal signed by Iraq and the
U.N. last May.
</P>
<P>
The deal allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S, dollars worth of
oil every six months to buy food and medicine urgently needed in
the country which is hit by the U.N.-imposed sanctions after its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been accusing the U.S. of "purposely and
unjustifiably" hampering the ratification in the U.N. Sanctions
Committee on Iraq of food and medicine contracts reached between
Iraq and foreign companies under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi diplomat also urged for increasing the number of
experts responsible for revising food and medicine contracts.
</P>
<P>
As for the U.N. Secretary-General, he stressed that he has
began to take measures to expedite the work for getting approved
the trade contracts submitted by Iraq to the sanctions
committee. And he himself would follow up this subject during
the coming days, said Annan.
</P>
<P>
Both Annan and Hamdoun agreed that the UNSCOM should be
committed to its assigned duties defined in accordance with
U.N. resolution 687, which is said to be limited to professional
and technical aspects only. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
