<HEADLINE> Albright Leaves for Home After Additional Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 2 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright wound up her two-day visit to Russia today
after postponing her departure for additional talks with her
Russian counterpart, Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The additional talks on Russian-NATO relations were held behind
closed doors at the request of Albright, who delayed her departure
scheduled for 11:00 a.m. Moscow time, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
No details of the talks were available. However, an agreement
between Russia and NATO still seems to remain an open question,
and military issues remain the most thorny ones for mutual
coordination.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived here Thursday, held talks with Primakov
soon after her arrival.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the talks, Primakov
said: "There is every reason to believe that the two sides want
the treaty on relations between Russia and NATO to be signed in
Paris on May 27."
</P>
<P>
He said the presidents of Russia and the United States were
interested in "continuing the talks in a constructive direction."
</P>
<P>
During her short visit, Albright also had a telephone
conversation with Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who backed the
intention of the two ministers to concentrate on the military
aspects of European security.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Albright that it was important to work in a
thorough way in drafting a document on Russia-NATO relations, and
especially to specify the understanding reached at the Helsinki
summit early this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
