<HEADLINE> German Tennis Star Stich to Retire in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 2 (Xinhua) -- German tennis star Michael Stich
announced Friday in Hamburg that he will retire at the end of the
season because of a long-time shoulder injury suffered since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Stich climbed to No. 2 rank worldwide in 1993, but he has
dropped to 26th.
</P>
<P>
The 1991 Wimbledom titlist and 1993 world champion said he had
thought about retiring after an injury in late 1995. A first-round
defeat at a Barcelona tournament last month triggered his decision.
</P>
<P>
Stich said he will play this year's French Open and Wimbledon
tournaments before ending his career in Germany's Davis Cup
relegation series against Mexico in September.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Stich helped Germany win the Davis Cup. He has won 18
ATP tour singles titles and nine in doubles.
</P>
<P>
Stich's downfall began October 20, 1995, when he tore a
ligament in Vienna playing Todd Woodbridge, the left ankle
twisting as he fell down writhing in agony. 
</P>
