<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, May 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain's opposition Labor Party swept to power
today, beating the ruling Conservatives with a biggest ever
victory in the general election.
</P>
<P>
With all but 30 seats counted, Labor has so far gained 417 in
the 659-seat lower house, beating the Conservatives on a scale
unseen in 165 years. Six cabinet ministers, including Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind and Defense Secretary Michael Portillo,
lost their seats.
</P>
<P>
John Major, who was ousted out of power in the elections,
announced today he would step down as the Conservative Party
leader.
</P>
<P>
Before departing to Buckingham Palace to hand his resignation
as prime minister to Queen Ilizabeth, he told reporters outside
No. 10 Downing Street, "When the curtain falls it is time to get
off the stage."
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African President Nelson Mandela today
left capital Pretoria for Pointe-Noire, Congo, where he will
accompany Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko to have face-to-face
peace talks with rebel leader Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure, Mandela told reporters that he believed
the Mobutu-Kabila talks, to be held on a South African naval ship
off the African coast later today, would result in some "forward
movement" in Zaire's peace process.
</P>
<P>
"If I was not positive, I would not be going," he said, adding
that both Mobutu and Kabila want a settlement and are aware of the
importance of the coming meeting.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
wound up her two-day visit to Russia today after postponing her
departure for additional talks with her Russian counterpart,
Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The additional talks on Russian-NATO relations were held behind
closed doors at the request of Albright, who delayed her departure
scheduled for 11:00 a.m. Moscow time, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
No details of the talks were available. However, an agreement
between Russia and NATO still seems to remain an open question,
and military issues remain the most thorny ones for mutual
coordination.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Over 20 people were feared killed when a tourist
bus fell into a 100 feet (about 33 meters) deep ditch in India's
Tamil Nadu state today, Press Trust of India reported.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated bus was stated to be carrying 57 tourists when
the accident took place. 
</P>
