<HEADLINE> Scholars Call for Popularization of Chinese Medicine in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A number of scholars in Hong Kong
today stressed the need to popularize the traditional Chinese
medicine in Hong Kong, noting that it is necessary to bring it
into the regular medical system here.
</P>
<P>
Opening a seminar on "Chinese Medicine -- Education, Research
and Application" held in the Chinese University of Hong Kong
(CUHK), Professor Leung Ping Chung, chairman of CUHK's Planning
Committee on Chinese Medicine Program, spoke on the development
and tendency of local education in Chinese Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Professor Arthur K C Li, vice-chancellor of the CUHK, told the
seminar that Chinese Medicine with its herbal preparations is
widely utilized among HK citizens. But the local government has
never brought it into the regular medical system in Hong Kong,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Li along with other participants of the seminar pointed out the
need to practise a more active scientific research and education
in traditional Chinese medicine and its popularization in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The topics discussed at the one-day seminar with participation
of more than 100 educators, researchers and practitioners included
"Immunomodulatory and Anti-Cancer Chinese Medicine," "Ganoderma,
Corilus and Other Medicinal Mushrooms," "Authentication, Quality
Control and Safety of Chinese Medicine," "Application of Gene
Cloning" and "Drug Quitting by Acupuncture Treatment."  
</P>
</TEXT>
