<HEADLINE> Blair Promises to Unite Britain Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new prime minister Tony
Blair today promised to "unite the nation" after 18 years of
Conservative rule and form "a government of practical measures."
</P>
<P>
In his first public speech outside his new home No. 10 Downing
Street, Blair told reporters and a crowd of cheering people, "We
have secured a mandate to bring this nation together, to unite as
one Britain, one nation."
</P>
<P>
A moment before he arrived at the Downing Street, Blair kissed
Queen Elizebath's hand in Buckingham Palace and accepted her
invitation to form a new government after John Major handed in his
resignation as prime minister to the Queen.
</P>
<P>
"For 18 years, 18 long years, my party has been in opposition.
It could only say, it could not do. Today we are charged with the
deep responsibility of government," the youngest British prime
minister of this century said.
</P>
<P>
"Today, enough of talking. It is time now to do."
</P>
<P>
The 44-year-old new prime minister said he realized the huge
responsibility on his should and promised "a government of
practical measures in pursuit of noble causes."
</P>
<P>
"The victory is a mandate for new Labor and not a return to the
past," he pledged, adding "The New Labor government will govern in
the interests of all people."
</P>
<P>
He also paid tribute to his rival and former prime minister
Major, saying he was a man of "decency and dignity."
</P>
<P>
Major had earlier left Downing Street. Before his departure,
he said in his farewell speech that he would resign as the
Conservative Party leader when a replacement was chosen.
</P>
<P>
With all but 26 of the 659 seats counted, the Labor Party was
on course for a majority of almost 180 seats, ensuring Blair a
comfortable majority in the parliament for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Turnout among the 44 million voters was 71.3 percent -- a
record post-war low. In the 1992 election, 77.7 percent of the
electorate voted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
