<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Following are business briefs from
the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates(UAE) is seeking more
investors for a mobile telephone satellite to expand the range of
telephone coverage in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Thuraya (chandelier) satellite venture has already
attracted seven shareholders from the UAE and other Arab
countries and more are expected to contribute this year, the
daily "Emirates News" quoted officials in charge of the project
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have conducted negotiations with new potential subscribers
from inside the Arab world and outside it", said the officials
from the UAE state-run Etisalat telecommunication company which
owns 26 percent of Thuraya to become the biggest shareholder of
the satellite.
</P>
<P>
"We expected them to announce their contribution to the
project after July", they said at MIDCOM, an international
telecommunication exhibition in Abu Dhabi, the UAE's capital.
</P>
<P>
"This will enable us to secure more funds for the project and
at the same time promote the satellite. This means that the
designed coverage areas will be expanded", they added.
</P>
<P>
New shareholder could come from India and other south and
southeast Asian countries, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The Thuraya satellite, the first in the UAE and the fifth in
the world, would cover the Middle East, North Africa, Turkey,
Iran, Pakistan, India, Bangladesh, Southern Europe and possibly
parts of southeast Asia, they said.
</P>
<P>
This means coverage could extend to South Korea, Thailand,
Indonesia, Singapore and other Asian countries, depending on the
market demand.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The prospect for the 7,000-year-old Egyptian textile
industry is gloomy as it has been cramped by hikes of cotton
price and lack of renovation.
</P>
<P>
Some even fear that the long-time industry is approaching the
verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The volume of textile exports, which represent about a quarter
of overall Egyptian exports, slumped by 21 percent to 2.5 billion
pounds (740 million U.S. dollars) in 1996 from 3 billion pounds
(880 million dollars) in 1995, according to a report by the
Committee of Industrial Production and Energy.
</P>
<P>
The limping industry is now fighting a losing war with its
fierce rivals in South Korea, Thailand, Taiwan, Turkey and
Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt failed to compete with the top 10 textiles exporters
whose collective exports reached 95 billion dollars in 1994, or
73.8 percent of the world's total textile exports.
</P>
<P>
Nor is it made to the list of the biggest 10 clothes
exporters, which distributed 81.7 billion dollars worth of
garments to the world markets.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A symposium on means of activating and stimulating
Egyptian exports will be held Sunday on the sidelines of the 22nd
International Conference of Statistics and Computer Science, the
English-language newspaper The Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Supply, Internal and External Trade Ahmed
Goweli will inaugurate the symposium which will discuss the role
of the state bodies in promoting Egyptian exports.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Trade Representation Sector Ahmed Khalid Hamdi and
some other government officials will attend the forum.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian government-sponsored structural adjustment
and economic reform programs are beginning to pay off, the latest
edition of the English weely Al-Ahram quoted an International
Monetary Fund (IMF) representative in Egypt as saying.
</P>
<P>
The representative, Arvind Subramanian, told the weekly just
days before an Egyptian government delegation is scheduled to
head for Paris for talks with leading donor country and
organizational officials, that "overall, the economy continues to
maintain a very sound and robust performance as fiscal
consolidation continues."
</P>
<P>
Since Egypt began implementing the IMF-inspired structural
adjustment and economic reform program in 1994, macro-economic
indicators have provided evidence that the first steps to reform
have already begun yielding results.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, by last February, had declined to 5.4 percent and
the budget deficit dropped to 0.8 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
These gains, however, should not be mistaken for the idea that
all roads will lead to increased reform, Subramanian said, adding
that the Egyptian government still needs to introduce a package
of reforms that will generate more investments and assure the
level of efficiency and productivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
