<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Autonomy of Minority Nationalities Fruitful in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The system of regional autonomy for
minority nationalities has been successful in China since Inner
Mongolia became the country's first autonomous region on May 1,
1947.
</P>
<P>
In Inner Mongolia, where Mongolians, Han Chinese, Manchus and
people of the Ewenki, Oroqen, Daur and Hui ethnic groups live
together in an area of 1.18 million sq km, the number of cadres of
ethnic minorities has soared to 169,700 from 7,000 shortly after
the founding of New China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
People of minority nationalities now account for 44 percent of
the leadership at various levels in Inner Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs of China's autonomous regions, prefectures, counties
and banners are all from the local ethnic minority groups, no
matter how small their populations are.
</P>
<P>
Respecting the languages and customs of different ethnic groups
and developing education in areas inhabited by ethnic minorities
are major indicators of equality among all nationalities.
</P>
<P>
In areas where the autonomy of minority nationalities
is practiced, one or more local languages are used.
</P>
<P>
At the congress of the Communist Party of China, the National
People's Congress and the meeting of National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, documents are
written not only in Han Chinese but also in the languages of seven
minority nationalities -- Mongolian, Tibetan, Uygur, Kazak,
Korean, Yi and Zhuang.
</P>
<P>
The Party and government have over the past decades attached
great importance to economic development in areas inhabited by the
ethnic minorities. Since the beginning of the reform and opening-up
drive in the late 1970s, the relatively more developed areas of
China have launched massive programs to assist the five autonomous
regions of Tibet, Inner Mongolia, Guangxi, Ningxia and Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
In Tibet most of the 62 projects supported by other parts of
the country have already been completed.
</P>
<P>
As the 21st century approaches, China's 55 ethnic-minority
nationalities are catching up with the rest of the country
rapidly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
