<HEADLINE> Major Drugs Trial Opens in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Hanoi People's Court today began
the high profile trial of 22 people alleged to be involved in the
country's biggest drug case.
</P>
<P>
Among the 22 accused, 11 were Vietnamese police officers and
border guards, including the Interior Ministry Police Captain, Vu
Xuan Truong.
</P>
<P>
The scandal dates back to January 1995 when two Lao nationals
were arrested in Vietnam after they were found in possession of 15
kg (30 pounds) of heroin.
</P>
<P>
One of the men offered information which led to the arrest of
about 30 people, and gained the informant a reprieve from
execution.
</P>
<P>
The trial, expected to last 10 days, would be much longer than
normal trials in the country.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has been plagued by drugs problems in recent years,
with new statistics showing that 200,000 of the country's 75
million population take drugs.
</P>
<P>
The government, which started a three-year anti-drug campaign
last year, is now struggling to control the spread of drug use and
trafficking in major cities, including Hanoi and the Ho Chi Minh
City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
