<HEADLINE> Record Field for HK's Tsing Ma Bridge Marathon Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A record field of over 5,500 local
and international runners are making their final preparations for
the historic Swire Group Tsing Ma Bridge Marathon and 10K-km Race
slated for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The field comprising over 900 marathoners and 4,600 10-km
runners, will inaugurate the Bridge -- the world's longest
suspension bridge carrying both road and rail traffic -- in a
spectacular style, the organizers claimed here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 international runners from 15 countries and regions
have arrived in Hong Kong to compete in the landmark event.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's national champion Peter de Vocht, 36, leads the men's
race, boasting a personal best time of two hours, 14 minutes and
54 seconds he created in 1992.
</P>
<P>
While for the women's division, it is Germany's Susan Bitzer, a
31-year-old pharmacist, who came out to be the hottest favored for
the title. Bitzer's personal best is 2:41:00.
</P>
<P>
But both felt the warm weather and higher humidity in Hong Kong
 pose a threat to their efforts for a better show.
</P>
<P>
"I'm used to cold climate and the temperature back to my home
town in Germany was just five degrees centigrade," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We had a snowfall two weeks ago and temperature at early
morning was below zero," said the former cross country skier.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to run or even to improve the personal best,"
admitted De Vocht. But he promised to give his best shot here.
</P>
<P>
Tsing Ma Bridge, the Kap Shui Mun Bridge and the Ma Wan viaduct
 which connects them form the Lantau Link, which is one of the key
 projects in Hong Kong's New Airport Core Program project.
</P>
<P>
Tsing Ma Bridge has a main span of 1,377 meters long and a
total length of 2.2 kilometers. A grand opening ceremony was held
 at the Bridge to celebrate the completion of construction of the
Lantau Link. 
</P>
</TEXT>
