<HEADLINE> New Round of Fighting in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 2 (Xinhua) -- At a time when the faction
leaders of Mogadishu are outside the country, the Somali capital
is experiencing a new round of fighting. One of the heaviest
clashes has taken place between the militiamen of Hussein Mohamed
Aidid and those of his south Mogadishu rival, Mr Osman Hassan Ali
Atto last night.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have again fought over the control of the
hostile strategic junction of k-7 linking Mogadishu to the
southern regions and the k-5 street near the headquarters of the
Somali Red Crescent Society and the former Care International
Compound. Both sides are reported to have suffered casualties.
However, hospital sources confirm the death of three people while
more than seven were treated of gun shot wounds.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at Dr Hassan Jis Memorial Hospital recorded the death
of a militiaman who was among the war victims they admitted into
the hospital last night. The doctors further more said that the
fighting last night has caused no heavy casualties since it was
taking place at late time when everybody was indoors.
</P>
<P>
Even though the intensity of the fighting has eased early in
the morning, the exchange of sporadic heavy shelling has
continued until 10:00 local time in the morning. The vibration of
the shelling from mortar rounds, the Russian made m-3, d-30 and
85 mm artillery rounds have however shook the walls of the nearby
residential areas of Hodon and Hawlwadag districts of south
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 12 people are believed to have died in the
renewed armed confrontations between the supporters of Hussein
Mohamed Aidid and those of Osman Ali Atto since the beginning of
the week. The reason for the renewed clashes between the two
sides is not yet known, however Osman Atto's faction has accused
Hussein Aidid's side for igniting the war. And as usual there's
no word yet from Hussein Aidid's side over the fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
