<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Seeks More Subscribers for Thuraya venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 2 (Xinhua) The United Arab Emirates(UAE) is
seeking more investors for a mobile telephone satellite to expand
the range of telephone coverage in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Thuraya (chandelier) satellite venture has already
attracted seven shareholders from the UAE and other Arab countries
and more are expected to contribute this year, the daily "Emirates
News" quoted officials in charge of the project as saying.
</P>
<P>
" We have conducted negotiations with new potential subscribers
from inside the Arab world and outside it", said the officials
from the UAE state-run Etisalat telecommunication company which
owns 26 percent of Thuraya to become the biggest shareholder of
the satellite.
</P>
<P>
" We expected them to announce their contribution to the
project after July", they said at MIDCOM, an international
telecommunication exhibition in Abu Dhabi, the UAE's capital.
</P>
<P>
"This will enable us to secure more funds for the project and
at the same time promote the satellite. This means that the
designed coverage areas will be expanded", they added.
</P>
<P>
New shareholder could come from India and other south and
southeast Asian countries, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The Thuraya satellite, the first in the UAE and the fifth in
the world, would cover the Middle East, North Africa, Turkey,
Iran, Pakistan, India, Bangladesh, Southern Europe and possibly
parts of southeast Asia, they said.
</P>
<P>
This means coverage could extend to South Korea, Thailand,
Indonesia, Singapore and other Asian countries, depending on the
market demand.
</P>
<P>
"Each shareholder may be responsible for marketing and
delivering the Thuraya personal communications services in his
home country. Other service providers who are not shareholders
now may also be considered (of being shareholders)," the Etisalat
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Etisalat said earlier that the services of Thuraya project,
the biggest telecommunication contract in the Middle East region
would include voice, data, fax and messaging.
</P>
<P>
The 850-million-dollar contract will be awarded in July and
the satellite will be put into orbit in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Three companies are competing for the deal after the French
Alcatel telecommunications giant has just been excluded. They are
Aerospatial of France, and Hughes and Locheed of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said at the MIDCOM that the Swedish
telecommunication company Ericsson would likely win a subcontract
to provide mobile phones for Thuraya. However, the speculation can
not be proved so far.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
