<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old-Young Pair Move Up in Men's Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANCHESTER, England, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Liu Guozheng, the
youngest member of the Chinese team, and Poland's Andrzej Grubba,
the oldest player in the world top 20 rankings, combined to crush
their rivals in the men's doubles first round at the World Table
Tennis Championships here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Chinese and the Polish veteran, who is to
celebrate his 39th birthday on May 14, beat the Belgian sibling
duo of Jean-Michael Saive and Jean-Philippe 21-18. 16-21, 21-19.
</P>
<P>
Liu has shown his strength by winning the Global Youth
Championship in February and Grubba has regained form after taking
the Malaysian Open last year.
</P>
<P>
The duo of different nationalities will take on China's
title-favorites Wang Liqin and Yan Sen, who made the second round
with an easy 21-11, 21-8 victory over Croatians Damir Atikovic and
Ivan Juzbasic.
</P>
<P>
Wang and Yan jumped to international stardom by taking the
doubles title at the French Open in November last year and they
rounded off the year by beating Jorg Rosskopf of Germany and
Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus to win the the Pro-Tour Finals in
December.
</P>
<P>
Rosskopf and Samsonov, tipped by Sweden's table tennis great
Jan-Ove Waldner as odds-on favorites here, also moved into the
second round with an easy win.
</P>
<P>
The duo had beaten reigning world champions Wang Tao and Lu Lin
and the Olympic gold medalists Liu Guoliang and Kong Linghui in
the Pro-Tour Finals.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tao and Ma Lin reached the second round with a straight
victory. Wang's longtime partner Lu Lin has retired from the
sport.
</P>
<P>
Top-seeded tandem of Kong and Liu and Sweden's second-seeded
pair of Waldner and Jorgen Persson moved into the second round
with a bye. 
</P>
</TEXT>
