<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Township Enterprises In South Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Township enterprises in south
China's Guangdong Province have scored a good start in the first
quarter of this year, by producing 65.4 billion yuan worth of
industrial output, or a year-on-year 23.5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Lin Jianrong, a township enterprise
administrator, as saying that the province's governments at all
levels have been developing township enterprises as one of the
most significant sectors in the rural economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Lin attributed the boom of the province's township enterprises
to the emphasis on the industrial sector at all levels of the
province's governments.
</P>
<P>
Lin took the city of Shantou as an example. The city has helped
its township enterprises win more shares in the domestic market by
holding product shows and economic cooperation seminars in China's
hinterland, and collected a domestic trade volume that rose by 15
percent as a result.
</P>
<P>
Zhongshan, a city in the Pearl River Delta, sponsored an
economic seminar in Hong Kong at the beginning of the year, and
secured a contractual overseas investment of 429 million US
dollars for 146 projects, as well as another 341 million US
dollars for 175 export trade contracts. The city's township
enterprises have been flooded with orders, some of which cannot be
filled out until year end.
</P>
<P>
Chaoyang city invested 265 million yuan into 103 pioneering
enterprises for expansion, equipment purchases, and renovations,
which led to an added output value of more than 80 million yuan in
the first two months.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Guangzhou, Zhaoqing, and Zhanjiang have all
laid out blueprints or specific priority policies to promote
township enterprises, Lin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
