<HEADLINE> Pakistan Expects 2.8 Billion Dollars of Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is expecting about 2.8
billion U.S. dollars of foreign aid from all resources including
the consortium in the 1997-98 fiscal year, Finance Minster Sartaj
Aziz said here today.
</P>
<P>
"This does not include the loans from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF)," Aziz said at a press conference held after
his return from an 8-day visit to Paris, Washington and New York.
</P>
<P>
"The consortium, the World Bank and the IMF, all strongly
supported our program of Economic reforms as bold and historical,"
Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Giving details about the financial commitments from all
resources, excluding the IMF, he said that about 70 percent of the
total commitments are from three resources -- the World Bank, the
Asian Development Bank and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the government was expecting from these
three resources around 1,700 million dollars which was about 300
million dollars more than the amount of last year.
</P>
<P>
Giving his account of engagements with officials of the IMF in
Washington, he said, the out-line of Staff Monitoring Program
(SMP), which was agreed upon with the IMF officials during their
visit to Pakistan in March, has been finalized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
