<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Taiwan Discuss Direct Shipping Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and Taiwan shipping
representatives met here today to discuss how to continue direct
shipping links after July 1, 1997, when China resumes its
exercises of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Technical problems for ships of one side to sail into ports of
the other were on the agenda of the one-day negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged views frankly and acknowledged that
Hong Kong and Taiwan should continue direct shipping after July 1,
1997. But they failed to reach any agreement on concerned details
of protocol.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both sides agreed to hold further
discussion on related issues in Taipei in the near future.
</P>
<P>
In a news briefing after the talks, George Chao, head of the
Hong Kong delegation said that today's negotiation was a good
beginning and laid a good foundation for further discussion.
</P>
<P>
Chao, who is also head of the Hong Kong Shipowners Association,
believed that these technical problems could be resolved timely
and properly so long as both sides observe the "One-China"
principle, take mutual benefits into account, and maintain a
practical and flexible attitude.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
