<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Expand Use of ISO Environmental Management Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to expand the use
of the standards of the International Standards Organization (ISO)
in environmental management, in a bid to get enterprises to put
resources to rational use and protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body, has approved
the establishment of a committee to promote this work. The
committee, whose members are leading officials from some 30
central government departments, will be headed by the director of
the State Bureau of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the standards, called ISO 14000, is to improve
management, and curb pollution and waste. Experts here held that
the standards will enable the country's environmental protection
to work more scientificly and effectively, and will coordinate the
development of the economy and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the SBEP said that China still has many
poorly-equipped factories, which contribute to pollution and waste
a lot of energy.
</P>
<P>
"The standards will help them to control pollution and waste in
the whole production process, while reducing the impact of human
activities on the environment," they said.
</P>
<P>
The standards are applicable to both modern factories and
outdated ones, sources said, revealing that four modern
enterprises have received ISO 14000 certificates, while another 22
are awaiting certification.
</P>
<P>
China started implementing the standards from April 1 this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
