<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher Buoyed By Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- A combination of the National
Australia Bank's impending interim result and Westpac Bank's share
buyback scheme helped propel the Australian share market to a
higher close today.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 6.2 points firmer at 2,491.6,
with the banking sector up 28.5 points to 4,387.0.
</P>
<P>
"The banks continue to be the strongest sector, National
Australia Bank was up the strongest out of all of the banks and
then Westpac Bank came in with that buyback scheme and that shot
their price above seven Australian dollars (5.46 US dollars),"
Jamie Spiteri of Show Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 0.4 points higher at 1,391.2,
while the all industrials jumped 13.1 points to 3,918.7.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the stocks tended to be steady to marginally
better.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 5.4 points higher at 1,557.6, with gold
bullion closing at 340.25 US dollars an ounce from 339.75
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 280.81 million shares traded, valued
at 744.19 million Australian dollars (580.46 million US dollars).
 
</P>
</TEXT>
