<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Further Market Declines Expected in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 2 (Xinhua) --The Philippine stock market fell
further Friday with its composite index sliding 42.52 points to
2,605, and analysts expect more declines in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
This is the third consecutive trading day the market suffered a
sharp decline.
</P>
<P>
The market crash started Tuesday when the 30-stock Philippine
composite index nose-dived 128.87 points, or 4.54 percent, to
2,708.44, the lowest level in two years.
</P>
<P>
After the biggest single-day drop in two years, the Central
Bank of the Philippines imposed the 20-percent limit on bank
lending to the property sector.
</P>
<P>
And as property is used as collateral for a loan in the
country, the central bank also ordered that banks should not lend
more than 60 percent of the appraised value of that property.
</P>
<P>
Despite the swift action by the central bank, the market fell
another 60.27 points, or 2.23 percent, to close at 2,648.17
Wednesday. There was no trading session on Labor Day Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Poor earnings of some big companies, including blue-chip
companies, in the first quarter and a possible economic slowdown
in the country could be partly attributed to the nose-dive in the
market, but the main reason for the sharp fall is investors' fear
of a property-related crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, the property index has
tumbled 17 percent while the overall market is down 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that investors have become increasingly concerned
that the Philippines could be hit by problems similar to those of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, years of excessive bank lending, estimated at over
30 percent of total portfolios, has led to over-supply of housing
units and a large amount of bad loans. In the capital Bangkok,
some 50 billion U.S. dollars worth of property is unsold,
abandoned or under construction. The number of vacant units in the
capital ranges from 385,000 to 400,000 at present.
</P>
<P>
With the collapse of a real estate bubble in Bangkok, banks and
finance companies are now struggling with 15.5 billion dollars of
bad loans.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, a central bank survey indicates that bank
lending to the property sector only accounted for 11 percent, but
individual bank exposure to the sector is as much as 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some economists predicted slower sales and earnings from many
of the property companies in the coming years. All Asia Securities
Management Corp. estimated in a property report that total new
supply will exceed total new demand by 211 percent in the year
2000 for residential developments, and by 142 percent for
commercial developments.
</P>
<P>
But many analysts still doubt that the Philippines is headed
for a Thai-style crisis as the problems, such as bank lending to
the property sector and property-related bad loans, are not as
serious as in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government also denied that a Thai-style crisis
would occur in the Philippines, saying that the higher U.S.
interest rates should be blamed for the market fall.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to allay fears of investors, President Fidel
Ramos told a press conference Wednesday that the nation's economy
is "very sound" despite the market decline and the pullout of some
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
"The pullout of some foreign investments in the equity market
is because of the rising interest rates in the United States,
meaning the investors have a better destination to go to because
of the promise of higher returns," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, many analysts believe that the market will continue to
suffer from an overhang from the poor corporate earnings and the
property sector concerns in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Trading will continue its bearish mode as market players wait
for fresh economic news and earnings of corporations in the
country, they said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, foreign fund managers are still waiting for the fate
of key interest rates in the United States with the next meeting
of the Federal Open Market Committee scheduled for May 20, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they said, the market is unlikely to make a quick
recovery in less than two weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
