<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to End Free College Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Tuition-free education for college
students will soon end in China as the country's remaining 368
free colleges and universities begin charging students fees this
year.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,032 colleges and universities in China, 664 stopped
providing free education last year and implemented the tuition
payment system, today's China Daily quoted a spokesman of the
State Education Commission (SEC) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The State will continue to provide loans, subsidies,
scholarships and work-for-study activities to those
financially-strained students to help them finish their college
study, said Zhao Jianjun, an official of the SEC's Financial
Department.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates show that about 20 percent of China's three
million college students come from financially-strapped families,
with an average monthly per capita income below 200 yuan (about 24
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
These students will be subsidized with State aid, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
He said that students specializing in agriculture, forestry,
water conservancy, education and geology, who are willing to work
in these fields after graduation, can receive special
scholarships, since the State is encouraging more students to
enter these sectors.
</P>
<P>
In China, the tuition system was first experimented in 40
colleges and universities in 1994 in an effort to reform free
college education that was a strain on State coffers, according to
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, each student is required to pay 1,500
yuan each year for tuition.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities can slightly adjust the tuition
standard according to their conditions, with the approval of local
educational administrations, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The system is also intended to unify various fee collection
standards in different colleges and universities, and stop those
unauthorized overcharges.
</P>
<P>
In the past, some colleges enrolled students who failed college
entrance exams because they paid money to the schools.
</P>
<P>
The money-based learning system resulted in a relatively poor
academic standards in these schools and created unfair competition
among students, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Such practice will be totally abandoned with the nationwide
implementation of a tuition system starting this fall semester, the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
