<HEADLINE> Major Announces Readiness to Quit as Party Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- John Major, who was ousted out of
power in Thursday's general election, announced today he would
step down as the Conservative Party leader.
</P>
<P>
Before departing to Buckingham Palace to hand his resignation
as prime minister to Queen Ilizabeth, Major told reporters
emotionally outside No. 10 Downing Street, "When the curtain falls
it is time to get off the stage."
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped a new Conservative leader would be found
fairly quickly "to lead the party through opposition in the years
ahead" but that he would remain at the Conservative service until
a replacement was chosen.
</P>
<P>
With all but 29 seats counted, the Labor Party was on course
for a landslide majority of almost 180 seats, ensuring Tony Blair
to govern Britain for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The defeat was on a scale unseen for 165 years with six cabinet
ministers, including Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind and Defense
Secretary Michael Portillo, losing their seats.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives were also left without any members of
parliament in Scotland and vast swathes of south-west England,
where the center-left Liberal Democrats inflicted most damage.
</P>
<P>
But Major said the Conservatives could be proud of their
achievements during the past 18 years and promised they would be
back.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the former Conservative prime minister Margaret
Thatcher expressed her disappointment today to the crushing defeat
of John Major.
</P>
<P>
"She is hugely disappointed. She has no plans to make any
further statement. She stayed up late into the night watching the
results," the local media quoted the Iron Lady's press secretary
Elizabeth Buchanan as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
