<HEADLINE> Yunnan Helps Farmers Achieve Prosperity Using Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
has introduced a computer software system in its 35
poverty-stricken counties to help them increase grain output and
plant high-return cash crops.
</P>
<P>
The system, named "Computer Agricultural Expert" and using
artificial intelligence, can provide advice on agriculture,
technology and economics, including seed strain selection and
fertilizer saving, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that the province plans to earmark 4.3
million yuan (about 500,000 US dollars) as a special fund for this
system every year.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan has been developing software in the field since 1992,
and has scored remarkable achievements in some pilot counties. In
Ninglang, an autonomous ethnic-minority county, the average
per-unit area yield of maize rose 9.3 percent, that of paddy rice
climbed 11.5 percent, and that of apples grew approximately 30
percent, figures show.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government also plans to spread the use of an
agricultural technology database from this year on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
