<HEADLINE> Ancient Relics Found in Downtown Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Many cultural relics found in
downtown Beijing in the past few months show that the city was
much colder 22,000-25,000 years ago, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Yue Shenyang, an ancient China expert from Beijing University,
drew the conclusion from the condition of the relics.
</P>
<P>
Yue was behind a major discovery at Wangfujing Street, where
about 23,000-year-old stone tools and bone fragment have been
unearthed from the Wangfujing construction site since December 28
last year.
</P>
<P>
Fissilized bones of elephants and of furred rhinoceros,
believed to be 20,000 and 40,000 years old, were also discovered
last month at the city center locations of Xidan and Chongwenmen.
</P>
<P>
Ostrich bones were found at the Wangfujing site and also
elephant bones thought to be of a species more common to African
than Asia, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
