<HEADLINE> Labor Urged to Redeem Promises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British Industry
(CBI) urged the imcoming Labor government to stick to what it
promised to do during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Labor's landslide victory of the General Election,
Adair Turner, Director-General of the CBI, said today: "The CBI
congratulates Labor on its historic election victory and on
forming the new Government."
</P>
<P>
Turner also said: "We welcome Labor's specific commitments on
inflation, personal tax and departmental spending levels, its
focus on the vital importance of improving an education system and
thus workplace skills, and its determination to ensure the
completion of the European Single Market."
</P>
<P>
However, Turner said, the challenge for the new government is
to maintain the economic background against which business can
succeed.
</P>
<P>
"Labor has pledged that it will, and now has the chance to
prove it," he added.
</P>
<P>
In opposition, Labor leader Tony Blair and his colleagues have
been keen to seek the views of business. Turner said: "CBI now
looks forward to working with them in Government to ensure that
the key messages are not lost."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the policies where CBI has concerns, Turner said
the priority is now to ensure that the government reflects
business interests in the detail of implementation.
</P>
<P>
"This will be vital with respect to the level of the minimum
wage, the extent and nature of the windfall tax and the details of
union recognition proposals," he stressed. 
</P>
