<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Kohl Visits Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
arrived in Port Douglas on Queensland's far north coast late today
for an official visit to Australia.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, accompanied by a 60-member delegation of German business
executives, was met by federal Industry Minister John Moore,
representing Prime Minister John Howard. He will spend the weekend
at Port Douglas.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's visit is part of a concerted push by Germany for closer
integration with the fast-growing Asia-Pacific economies. He will
travel to Canberra Sunday ahead of official talks with Howard next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said the visit represented a major
opportunity to expand Australia's level of trade and investment
activity with Germany, which is Australia's ninth largest overall
source of foreign investment and eighth largest trading partner.
</P>
<P>
Howard is expected to discuss with the chancellor Australia's
greenhouse reduction proposal. He planned to raise the issue with
every foreign leader he could find ahead of a global summit in
December in Japan at which an international agreement on stronger
emission reduction measures is to be signed.
</P>
<P>
Australia is opposing binding targets on the grounds it would
significantly harm the economy because of its heavy reliance on
fossil fuels, proposing instead a model that takes into account
each country's particular circumstances in setting emissions
reduction goals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
