<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Increase Cotton Growing Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has set a target of growing
28,000 hectares of cotton this year, 83,000 by 2000 and 120,000 by
2010, an official report said today.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, cotton areas stood at 15,000 hectares, including 3,500
hectares of hybrids, with an average yield of 1.2 to 1.3 ton per
hectare compared to an average productivity of 0.7 tons for other
varieties.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's annual yarn output is expected to reach 50,000 tons
by the year 2000 and to be doubled ten years later, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The current yarn production of 4,000 tons a year can only meet
10 percent of the demand of Vietnam's textile industry, which has
to spend 120 million U.S. dollars annually importing textile
materials including cotton, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Tran Duc Luong said the foremost task is
to give growers access to more cotton varieties, particularly
hybrids.
</P>
<P>
He said in 1997 and 1998, a loan from the International
Monetary Fund would be used to build modern cotton processing
plants in key cotton growing provinces in Vietnam's central
highlands and the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
