<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Leaves for Meeting With Mobutu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela today left capital Pretoria for Pointe-Noire, Congo where
he will accompany Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko to have
face-to-face peace talks with rebel leader Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure, Mandela told reporters that he
believed the Mobutu-Kabila talks, to be held on a South African
naval ship off the African coast later today, would result in
some "forward movement" in Zaire's peace process.
</P>
<P>
"If I was not positive, I would not be going," he said, adding
that both Mobutu and Kabila want a settlement and are aware of
the importance of the forthcoming meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kabila reportedly said yesterday while visiting Harare,
Zimbabwe that his forces will continue to march on Kinshasa
despite the planned peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He also said he had been told the talks had been postponed to
Saturday because "Mobutu had changed his mind again."
</P>
<P>
However, South African presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana
said this morning that the talks will still go ahead today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Foreign Minister Alred Nzo reportedly will meet
Mobutu in Pointe-Noire before accompanying him to the South
African naval ship SAS Outeniqua.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and
Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad met Kabila in Luanda, Angola
this morning before departing for the ship talks.
</P>
<P>
United Nations special envoy Mohamed Sahnoun and Congolese
President Pascal Lissouba will also attend today's talks,
informed sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
