<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Labor Party Wins in General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Labor Party swept to
power early Friday, beating the ruling Conservatives with a
biggest ever victory in the general election.
</P>
<P>
With all but 30 seats counted, Labor has so far gained 417
in the 659-seat lower house, beating the Conservatives on a
scale unseen in 165 years. Six cabinet ministers, including
Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind and Defense Secretary Michael
Portillo, lost their seats.
</P>
<P>
"A new dawn has broken, has it not? And it is wonderful. We
always said that if we had the courage to change then we could do
it. And we did it," Blair, the 43-year-old would-be British prime
minister told a large crowd of cheering supporters with a broad
smile early Friday morning in the Royal Festival Hall on the bank
of the River Thames.
</P>
<P>
"Today on the eve of this new millennium the British people
have ushered in this new era of politics," said Blair, who became
the Labor leader three years ago after his predecessor died of a
sudden heart attack and has reformed his party to a "new Labor"
since.
</P>
<P>
"We will work with business to create that dynamic and
enterprising economy we need and we will work with all our people
for that just and decent society the British people have wanted
for so long," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the main reason for Blair to win a landslide
victory was that voters wanted a change as they were fed up with
the 18-year rule of the Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the sleaze and sex scandals of senior government
officials and the division of the Conservatives over Europe, which
dominated the election campaign, have turned the traditional
voters away.
</P>
<P>
Even though Prime Minister John Major himself was re-elected
member of parliament in his Huntingdon constituency, he looked
shocked to see the terrible result and conceded the defeat.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight we have been comprehensively defeated. Let us not
pretend to ourselves it was anything other than what it was," said
Major, who had remained optimistic and confident to win the
election till the end of the 46-day campaign.
</P>
<P>
Although Blair won a comfortable victory in the election, his
inexperience in government office will put him in the uncharted
water immediately and test his ability as head of government.
</P>
<P>
The toughest early test will be in foreign arena when
Blair goes to three summits in June and July -- the European
Union, the Group of Seven industrialized nations, and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"It's just a new beginning, not an end," one of Blair's
close aides said early Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
