<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Counts on Britain's Labor for Cooperation over Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- France today hoped Britain's Labor
Party of Tony Blair, which has won a historic victory over the
Conservative Party in the general election, to offer more
cooperation over European construction.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of European Affairs Michel Barnier said that
the victory of the Labor Party will allow France to "win an ally
for constructing the social dimension of Europe."
</P>
<P>
"This is an election which is naturally important for the
British themselves, who have turned the page of 18 years of
Conservative management, as well as an important election for all
European countries," said Barnier.
</P>
<P>
France will hold its general election on May 25 and June 1, in
which the Maastricht Treaty of the European Union on the launching
of the monetary union will become one important element for
voting. Now the debates about it are underway between the ruling
center-right majority and the left-wing oppositions.
</P>
<P>
Barnier said that the new government will give Britain more
force in a series of important events over European construction
in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
"My impression is that Tony Blair sees European construction in
a more positive way (than John Major) for the interests of
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, First Secretary of the French Socialist Party Lionel
Jospin congratulated the Labour Party for what he called "a
magnificent victory" in the general election.
</P>
<P>
French Communist Party national secretary Robert Hue said that
the victory of the Labor Party is a "satisfying result for all
those who fight against ultra-liberalism."
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain has experienced a "horrible social purge"
under the Conservative Party from 1979.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed doubt over whether Blair will bring about
"big changes in all the fields of economic and social policy,"
adding "to put an end to Thatcherism is an important thing."
</P>
</TEXT>
