<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Labour Day became a real festival for the
British Labour Party, whose leader Tony Blair will be Britain's
new prime minister as his party has won a massive victory in the
general election.
</P>
<P>
-- Tony Blair will have little time to wait to decide on one of
the most explosive questions in Britain -- whether to join the
European single currency, Euro. With only six weeks away from the
European summit to be held in Amsterdam which will decide on the
reform of European institutions, Blair is expected to take a
prudent position on the Euro because of the strong opposition by
the British to the monetary union.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Despite the victory by the Labour Party of Tony Blair, the
revolution brought to Britain 18 years ago by the Conservative
Party under Margaret Thatcher is irreversible. In 18 years,
Britain has experienced the changes of a century by abandoning its
state welfare and adapting itself to the rules of free market.
</P>
<P>
-- The British Labour Party will announce its government today
in which Tony Blair will have four heavy-weight ministers: Robin
Cook as foreign secretary, Gordon Brown as chancellor of
exchequer, David Blunkett as education secretary, and John
Prescott as secretary of transport and environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
