<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Value of Production Index Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The value of production index (VPI)
in the Philippines' key manufacturing enterprises increased 0.1
percent to 453 in February 1997 from 452.5 a year ago, official
statistics showed today.
</P>
<P>
On a month-on-month comparison, VPI increased 10.4 percent from
410.4 in January this year, according to figures based on the
results of a survey of key manufacturing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was conducted by the National Statistics
Office, aims to provide flash indicators on the performance of the
country's key manufacturing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Double-digit month-on-month increases were observed in the
sectors of electrical machinery, transport equipment, food
manufacturing and textiles, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Basic metals highly affected VPI growth on a month-on-month
basis contributing 82.1 percent to the negative effects on the
growth basis, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
It also indicated year-on-year increases in the sectors of
electrical machinery, wood and wood products, chemicals and
non-metallic products.
</P>
<P>
The volume of production index (VoPI) also increased 10 percent
in February from 137.8 in January 1997, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
The VoPI is derived from VPI and producer's price index with
1992 as the base year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
