<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Comrade Peng Zhen was a great
proletarian revolutionary and statesman, an outstanding activist
in state affairs, a staunch Marxist, a principal founder of
China's socialist legal system and an outstanding leader of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and the state. His life was a
brilliant one of a revolutionary. He had firmly struggled for and
made indelible historical contributions to the liberation of the
Chinese People and the founding of the new China, the cause of
socialist revolution and the construction and the ultimate
realization of communism.
</P>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen was born into a poor peasant family in
Dieshang Village, Houma Town, Quwo County, Shanxi Province, on
October 12, 1902, and was named Fu Maogong. After joining the
revolution, he used many aliases in underground work. Until in
1937, he changed his name as Peng Zhen.
</P>
<P>
In his childhood, Peng Zhen followed his parents in laboring in
the fields in daytime, and joined his whole family in spinning
cotton into threads at night, weathering all the hardship of
life. He once, along with his grandmother and out of anger, rose
to resist suppression by a local despot.
</P>
<P>
Because the poverty of his family, Peng attended an old-style
private school till he was 12. In 1919, he was admitted into the
No. 2 Advanced Primary School of Quwo County after an examination,
where under the influence of the "May 4th Movement," he led his
schoolmates in carrying out patriotic publicity activities against
imperialism.
</P>
<P>
He passed the entrance examination to the No. 1 Provincial
Middle School of Shanxi Province in 1922, where he endeavored
himself to seeking a path to save the country and the Chinese
people. He joined a progressive organization, the Youth Society,
and accepted Marxism.
</P>
<P>
Peng Zhen joined the Socialist Youth League of China in 1923
and joined the CPC the same year, and was one of the founding
members of the Communist Party organization in Shanxi
Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the period of the Great Revolution in China (1924-1927)
Peng Zhen organized and led movements of workers and students in
Taiyuan, Shijiazhuang, Tianjin, Tangshan and other places, serving
as a member and secretary of the CPC's Taiyuan Branch, secretary
of the Taiyuan Prefectural Committee of the Communist Youth League
of China, secretary of the second, first and third district
committees of the CPC's Tianjin Prefectural Committee,
respectively, head of the Organization Department of the CPC's
Tianjin Prefectural Committee and as a member of the Workers
Movement.
</P>
<P>
In 1923, he helped set up a night school mainly for workers in
Taiyuan, and took part in organizing the fight against Cao Kun's
corrupt election practices and the establishment of the Great
league of Taiyuan Civil Rights Movements.
</P>
<P>
In 1924, he took part in making preparations for the
establishment of the Shanxi Provincial Committee of the Kuomintang
(KMT) to promote cooperation between the KMT and the CPC, carried
out struggles against the activities of the KMT right-wingers to
repel Communists, and organized the founding of the promotion
committees of the National Council in Taiyuan City and Shanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
In 1925, Peng Zhen directed the founding of the Shanxi
Federation of Workers and the Taiyuan Federations of Trade Unions,
and mobilized workers and people from all walks of life in a
struggle against Yan Xishan's forced imposition of a residence tax
and called upon the people of Shanxi to support the
anti-imperialist struggle of the Shanghai workers and students
after the May 30 Massacre. In Shijiazhuang, he helped restore the
Federation of Trade Unions of the Zhengzhou-Taiyuan Railway, and
served as its secretary.
</P>
<P>
In 1926, he participated in the third National Congress of
Railway Workers in Tianjin as the delegate of the Federation of
Trade Unions of the Zhengzhou-Taiyuan Railway. He organized
several workers' moverments in cotton mills in Shijiazhuang and
Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
After the failure of the Great Revolution, Peng Zhen served as
one of the principal CPC leaders in northern China, holding the
posts respectively as the acting secretary and secretary of the
CPC Tianjin City Committee, member of the Standing Committee of
the CPC Shunzhi Provincial Committee, head of its Organization
Department and acting secretary of the provincial committee (The
CPC Shunzhi Provincial Committee at that time led the work
of the party organizations in Beiping, Hebei, Shanxi, Shandong,
Chahar, Henan and other North China areas).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under the harsh conditions of the White terror, he went deep
among the masses of workers to persist in the struggle for
liberation. He organized and led peasants in the suburbs of
Tianjin in their struggles against despots and for the protection
of tenant peasants. He also recruited new Party members from among
the peasants.
</P>
<P>
He was betrayed by traitors and arrested in Tianjin in 1929,
but he did not yield despite torture. He organized comrades in
prison to fight against traitors and special agents of the enemy,
thus reducing the loss of the Party to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
He secretly set up a CPC branch in prison and served as its
secretary, where he organized studies and publicity of Marxism,
and carried out struggles in various forms.
</P>
<P>
Released in 1935 after serving his prison term, Peng Zhen
served as a leader of the CPC working group in Tianjin and
organized people from all walks of life there in carrying out
movement against Japanese aggression and for national salvation.
</P>
<P>
In 1936 he worked as the representative of the CPC Central
Committee's North China Bureau and head of its Organization
Department, and directly led the headquarters of the Chinese
National Liberation Vanguard Corps. He supported the basic
principles and tactics put forward by Comrade Liu Shaoqi regarding
work in the White areas, adhered to the Party's policies regarding
the national united front against Japanese aggression, and
criticized and corrected the erroneous trends of closed-doorism,
adventurism and capitulationism.
</P>
<P>
He played an important role in restoring and developing CPC
organizations in northern China, consolidating and enhancing the
achievements of the "December 9" patriotic movement, vigorously
promoting the formation of the national united front against
Japanese aggression and creating a new situation in the work in
the White area.
</P>
<P>
In May 1937 Peng Zhen attended a Party national conference of
delegates held in Yan'an in the capacity of chairman of the White
area delegation, and was elected a member of the presidium of the
Party conference.
</P>
<P>
He stressed in a speech at the conference that the Party must
make full use of the united front in the White area to organize
and fully arouse the masses to action against Japanese aggression,
and at the same time uphold the independence of the Party.
</P>
<P>
Later he attended the White Area Work Conference held by the
CPC Central Committee and a meeting of the Political Bureau of the
Party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
After hearing Comrade Mao Zedong elaborate on the basic issues
of the Chinese revolution and the philosophical ideas of Maxism,
and at the same time taking into consideration the experiences and
lessons of the Chinese revolution, Peng Zhen recognized that
Comrade Mao Zedong fully deserved his position as the leader of
the Communist Party of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the War of Resistance Against Japanese Aggression broke
out, Comrade Peng Zhen was engaged in arranging the Party's work in
the guerrilla warfare and founding anti-Japanese bases in north
China. In 1938 he served as secretary of the Shanxi-Chahar-Hebei
Sub-Bureau (the Northern Sub-Bureau) of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Along with Comrade Nie Rongzhen and others, he contributed to
the development and consolidation of the Shanxi-Chahar-Hebei
Anti-Japanese Base, and creatively implemented the strategic
principles and fundamental policies of the Party Central Committee
regarding the War of Resistance Against Japanese Aggression.
</P>
<P>
While going all out to mobilize the masses and expand the
people's forces, he set forth and implemented policies concerning
the building of the Party, political power and the army in the
revolutionary bases, as well as policies regarding land, economy,
labor, finance, and so on.
</P>
<P>
He was also in charge of drawing up the "Current
Administrative Program of the Northern Sub-Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee for the Shanxi-Chahar-Hebei Border Region".
</P>
<P>
He explicitly set forth the idea that "Marxism should be
adapted to China", and that work should be done to "reform the old
society and build a society of new democracy" in the revolutionary
bases.
</P>
<P>
The Presidium of the enlarged Sixth Plenum of the Sixth CPC
Central Committee praised the Shanxi-Chahar-Hebei Border Region as
a "model anti-Japanese base in the enemy's rear area" and a "model
region for the united front".
</P>
<P>
In 1941 Comrade Peng Zhen made a report in Yan'an to the
Political Bureau of the Party Central Committee and Comrade Mao
Zedong on various concrete policies of the Shanxi-Chahar-Hebei
Border Region, as well as the region's experience in Party
building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the report he analyzed the political tendencies of various
classes and strata in the border region, and explained the grounds on
which Party organizations in the region had formulated various
basic policies, as well as the different focuses of policy
implementation in different periods. He made a comprehensive
and systematic summary of the basic experience in the building of
the border region on the basis of combining theory with practice.
</P>
<P>
His report was highly praised by Comrade Mao Zedong, who called
it a "Marxist report." The report was recommended and distributed
by the Party Central Committee to the Party committees in all
other revolutionary bases for reference.
</P>
<P>
After that Comrade Peng Zhen began to work on the Party
Central Committee, serving as dean of studies and vice-president
of the Party School of the CPC Central Committee and head of the
Organization Department and Urban Work Department of the CPC
Central Committee. He also took part in leading the rectification
movement in Yan'an.
</P>
<P>
In 1944 he attended the enlarged Seventh Plenum of the Sixth
CPC Central Committee, and as member of the History Report
Committee and Organization Committee, participated in the drafting
of the "Resolution on Some Historical Issues" and the
"Report on the Revision of the Party Constitution".
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Yan'an he made significant contributions to
summarizing the Party's historical experience, unifying the whole
Party's thinking on the correct line represented by Comrade Mao
Zedong, setting the leading position of the Mao Zedong Thought
within the whole Party, training senior leaders for the Party, and
carrying out the Party's underground work in areas occupied by the
enemy or under the rule of the Kuomintang.
</P>
<P>
In 1945 he attended the Seventh National Congress of the CPC,
at which he was elected a member of the Presidium and chairman of
the Credentials Committee.
</P>
<P>
At the congress he delivered a speech titled "On Urban Work in
the Enemy-Occupied Areas", in which he summarized the Party's
historical experience in carrying out underground struggle, and
expounded a series of principles, policies and strategies, such as
keeping a small but highly competent team, acting covertly, and
uniting the masses and accumulating strength by legitimate
means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the Seventh National Congress of the CPC and the First
Plenum of the Seventh CPC Central Committee, he was elected member
of the Central Committee and the Central Committee's Political
Bureau. In August of the same year, he became alternate member of
the Secretariat of the Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Following the victory of the War of Resistance Against Japanese
Aggression, Comrade Peng Zhen served as secretary of the
Northeastern Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and political
commissar of the Democratic Amalgamated Army of the Northeast,
with the task to realize the Party's strategic decision made at
the CPC Seventh National Congress to gain the control of the
northeast China.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances of complicated contradictions and
rapidly-changing situations, he had earnestly carried out
decisions, instructions and orders of the Party Central Committee,
the Central Military Commission and Chairman Mao Zedong, and
defeated the military attacks by the Kuomintang reactionaries.
</P>
<P>
He also fully mobilized the masses, enhanced the people's
strength, expanded the army rapidly, and set up bases, laying a
foundation for the final victory.
</P>
<P>
In 1947, he returned to the Party Central Committee, served as
member of the Standing Committee of the Work Committee of the CPC
Central Committee, and guided the work of the Shanxi-Chahar-Hebei
region as a member of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The next year he became head of the Organization Department and
director of the Policy Research Office of the CPC Central
Committee. In December of the same year, he started to serve
concurrently as secretary of the CPC Beiping Municipal Committee.
</P>
<P>
In September of 1949, he participated in the first Plenum of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) as
one of the representatives of the CPC, and was elected member of
the CPPCC National Committee and the Central People's Government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen performed immortal feats for the victory of
the Chinese revolution and the founding of the People's Republic
of China.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of New China, Comrade Peng Zhen held
leading posts in the Party and the state for a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
In early years after the founding of the People's Republic, he
served as a member of the Central People's Government, deputy
director and secretary of Leading Party Members' Group of the
Politics and Law Committee under the Government Administration
Council, and later head of the Politics and Law Group of the Party
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1954, he served as vice-chairman of the Standing
Committees of the First, Second and Third National People's
Congresses, as well as vice-chairman of the Second, Third and
Fourth CPPCC National Committees.
</P>
<P>
At the Eighth CPC National Congress and the First Plenum of the
Eighth CPC Central Committee held in 1956, he was elected a member
of the Central Committee, Political Bureau and Secretariat of the
Central Committee, assisting Comrade Deng Xiaoping to run the
Secretariat of the Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of New China, he served concurrently as
secretary of the CPC Beijing Municipal Committee, and also served
as mayor of Beijing from 1951 to May 1966.
</P>
<P>
During the 17 years after the founding of New China, as a
member of the collective leadership of the Party and the state
headed by Mao Zedong, he made painstaking efforts for and made
outstanding contributions to the building of the Party and the
political power, economic construction, political and
legal work, united front work, work concerning ethnic minorities,
ideological and theoretical work, and work in science,
education, culture and foreign affairs, as well as the
construction and development of the national capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (8) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the process of liberating Beijing Comrade Peng Zhen did
a good job of combining the consistency of principles with the
flexibility of tactics. Relying on the working class and the
laboring masses and uniting with all the non-Communist parties and
personages without party affiliation, as well as with
intellectuals and all other forces that could be united with, in a
short period of time he cleaned up the filth and mire left over
from the old society and established a new social order in
Beijing, achieving a great social and historical change that shook
the world.
</P>
<P>
Before Liberation Beijing was a consumer-oriented city mired in
destitution and devastation. Shortly after the liberation of
Beijing, Peng Zhen emphasized that restoration, transformation and
development of production should be taken as the central task for
Party organizations, government bodies and military units and the
citizens in Beijing; all the other work should be arranged around
and subordinated to this central task.
</P>
<P>
He explicitly pointed out that the construction of the capital
should serve the cause of the people and production, as well as
the Party Central Committee and departments of Central People's
government. By 1951 Beijing's economy had fully recovered and
topped the previous records.
</P>
<P>
With the socialist transformation of the ownership of the means
of production, Beijing achieved rapid progress in economic
construction, and changed from a consumer-oriented city into a
production-oriented one.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after he entered the city, Peng Zhen started working on
urban planning for the capital, and in 1956 put forth the guiding
principle that "urban planning should be conducted from a
long-term perspective, with the prospects for socialism taken into
consideration and room left for development by future
generations." In 1958 Peng Zhen led the construction of ten major
buildings and the planning for the construction of the Tiananmen
Square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the course of socialist construction, Peng Zhen not only
cherished people's enthusiasm for building socialism, but also
stressed "we must and can only do our work by practically and
earnestly following the objective law."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that investigation and study were essential for
avoidance of ideological mistakes in terms of line in socialist
construction. Ernestly practicing what he advocated, Peng Zhen
went down to the countryside and factories to listen to the
opinions of the masses, and made investigations and study.
</P>
<P>
Planning meticulously and making painstaking efforts during the
17 years, Peng Zhen made great contributions to building the
capital into a modern socialist city.
</P>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen had always paid respect to knowledge and
talents, and attached utmost importance to the development of
scientific, educational and cultural undertakings. He emphasized
that Beijing was the national cultural center with a cluster of
higher education institutions, and it was of great significance to
run such institutions well.
</P>
<P>
He led the formulation of a decision on improving the educating
quality of middle and primary schools in Beijing. Showing great
concern over the healthy growth of the young, he made speeches to
college graduates in the capital for many consecutive years. In
the speeches, he encouraged the graduates to conscientiously take
the inevitable historical road, integrate themselves with workers
and peasants and steadfastly follow the Communist Party,
whole-heartedly serve the people and socialism.
</P>
<P>
Peng Zhen put forward the idea of "developing literature and
art for the broad masses of people in cities", urging writers and
artists to go down to the factories as they had gone down to the
countryside to reflect the new age after a victory nationwide had
been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the "Great Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976), Comrade
Peng Zhen was wrongly criticized and cruelly persecuted by Lin
Biao and Jiang Qing and their like, and was stripped of all his
posts inside and outside the Party and lost his personal
freedom. Even under these circumstances he still persisted in
studying Marxism-Leninism and Mao Zedong Thought, summed up
historical experience, was concerned about and thought deeply
about the future and destiny of the Party and State, and fought
resolutely against Lin Biao and Jiang Qing and their like. After
the Third Plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee, the CPC
Central Committee announced that "all the charges, slanders and
libels imposed on Comrade Peng Zhen during the 'Great Cultural
Revolution' should be repudiated."
</P>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen pointed out at the first meeting of the
Central Committee he attended after his rehabilitation: "We must
adhere to holding high the banner of Marxism-Leninism and Mao
Zedong Thought, otherwise there will be chaos in the ideology of
the whole Party, the whole army and the people of all ethnic
groups, as well as on the entire revolutionary front, which will
 sadden our own people and gladden the enemy. Great attention must
be paid to the ideological trend of liberalization. But our
determination to expand democracy within the Party and people's
democracy must never waver, nor should we waver in our resolve to
adhere to the correct ideological line of seeking truth from
facts, emancipating our minds and using social practice as the
criterion of testing truth.
</P>
<P>
In September 1979, Comrade Peng Zhen was elected at the Fourth
Plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee as a member of the CPC
Central Committee and a member of the Political Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee. Later he was re-elected a member of the 12th
CPC Central Committee and a member of the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee. In 1980 he was appointed secretary of the
Politics and Law Committee of the CPC Central Committee. At the
Second Session of the Fifth National People's Congress (NPC) in
June 1979, Peng Zhen was elected vice-chairman of the NPC Standing
Committee and concurrently chairman of the NPC's Law Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He also raised the idea of "weeding through the old to bring
forth the new", which meant the remodeling of traditional drama forms
and their improvement in the course of remodeling.
</P>
<P>
He often went deeply into education, science and technology,
literary and art circles to make many friends and solicit
opinions. He respected and united with older intellectuals, and
cared for and cultivated younger ones, attaching great importance
to giving full scope to their role in socialist construction.
</P>
<P>
In 1965, when the cultural field was already seriously affected
by the ``Left''tendency, Peng Zhen pointed out clearly that
political issues must be differentiated from academic and art
issues; the truth must be tested by social practice; everyone, no
matter what one's station in life is, must uphold the truth and be
ready to correct mistakes -- and all are equal before the truth.
</P>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen gave prominence to the building of the ruling
party, regarding it as crucial to the success of all socialist
undertakings.
</P>
<P>
In 1950 he raised before the whole Party the issue of
preventing corruption in the Party under the new circumstances,
noting that to ensure that the Party should never become corrupt
depended on: first, political, organizational and ideological
purity; second, close contact with the masses and supervision by
the masses; third, criticism and self-criticism; and fourth, the
system, laws and discipline.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that an important principle in ensuring that no
disaster would happen to the Party was reliance on a collective
leadership and adherence to democratic centralism. He required
Party organizations and members in Beijing to "stand in the
forefront of revolution and construction", and to "set the highest
standards for our work that can possibly be met."
</P>
<P>
He said that shortcomings and mistakes in work must be
acknowledged, and what was right and what was wrong should be
admitted honestly. This was the nature of the Communist Party. One
should tell no lies, conceal no shortcomings or mistakes, still
less gloss over one's faults, conceal one's faults for fear of
criticism, or hold back unpleasant information.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out emphatically that bureaucracy did enormous harm
to people and would lead to the destruction of the country. He
also warned that all Party members and cadres, especially leading
cadres, should resolutely get rid of the bureaucratic style of
work characterized by being divorced from the masses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (12) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the First Session of the Sixth NPC in June, 1983, Peng Zhen
was elected chairman of the NPC Standing Committee. In the new
historical era, as an important member of the collective
leadership of the Party and State with Comrade Deng Xiaoping at
the core, he participated in a series of policy-making decisions
of the Party and State, thereby making great contributions to
bringing order out of chaos, and to establishing and implementing
the Party's basic line of taking economic construction as the
center and adhering to the four cardinal principles and reform and
opening-up, to building socialism with Chinese characteristics,
and to the reunification of the motherland and the unity of all
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized time and again: "The focus of the work of the
State should be resolutely shifted to socialist economic
construction and modernization drive, and all work must center
around and serve this focal point"; "The four cardinal principles
reflect the historical development laws independent of man's will
and are a decisive choice made by hundreds of millions of Chinese
people in their long-term struggle"; "To adhere to the four
cardinal principles under the new historical circumstances, it is
imperative to combine the universal truth of Marxism with the
concrete practice of China's socialist construction, and to blaze
a path of socialist construction with Chinese characteristics";
"The essence of Marxism-Leninism and Mao Zedong Thought is
critical and revolutionary, and socialism in essence requires
constant reform, development and improvement"; Reform and opening
up "is a reflection of objective laws and a conclusion drawn from
the summarization of the practical experience of our country in
the past 30-odd years. It will not change"; "Without developing a
commodity economy, the Chinese economy can not be
rejuvenated. This should be perceived from a strategic perspective
and be adhered to firmly".
</P>
<P>
In his later years, in spite of his advanced age, Peng Zhen
often went down to the grass-roots for investigation and study. He
was greatly concerned about the development of the special
economic zones and he inspected them repeatedly. On an inspection
tour of Shenzhen and Zhuhai in 1987 he pointed out that "The
special economic zones are successful and the direction is
right. Special economic zones should be allowed to pilot
experiments and reform bravely. The special economic zones must
vigorously develop the social productive forces and an
export-oriented economy, adhere to the four cardinal principles,
continue reform, open up wider and further revitalize themselves."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peng Zhen's Glorious, Militant Life (13) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Comrade Peng Zhen was for a long time in charge of and led the
work of building socialist democracy and legal system. In 1954 he
participated in drawing up New China's first Constitution, and
made a profound exposition at the First Session of the First
National People's Congress on the basic legal principle that
everybody is equal before the law as defined in the Constitution.
He presided over the work of drafting some other laws, including
the Criminal Law. When he was persecuted during the "Great
Cultural Revolution" (1966-1976), Peng made an in-depth study of
the building of China's democracy and legal system. He worked
untiringly day and night after the Third Plenum of the 11th CPC
Central Committee, and took charge of formulating seven important
laws in three months, including China's first Criminal Law and the
Law of Criminal Procedure. In 1980 he personally directed the
revision of the Constitution, as vice-chairman of the Committee
for Revision of the Constitution. Since 1979, a series of basic
statutes were drafted under his guidance, involving the state
institutions, civil and criminal laws, lawsuit procedures, and
economic and laws involving overseas, which have laid solid
foundations for China's socialist legal system. He put forward
many important ideas for the building of China's socialist legal
system, pointing out that the Chinese people handled affairs by
relying mainly on policies during the revolutionary war, while
they not only relied on policies but also on laws in doing their
daily work after the people took over the country's political
power. This was a historic shift; A sound building of a socialist
legal system must be centered on economic construction, and
efforts must be made to adhere to the four cardinal principles and
reform and opening-up, and serve the building of socialism with
Chinese characteristics. The work of legislation must be done
under the guidance of Marxism, and by taking China's conditions
into account, summing up China's own practical experience, and
meanwhile learning from what benefits the Chinese people from the
ancient and modern, China and elsewhere, he added; state
institutions at all levels must handle affairs strictly according
to laws, let the masses of people know the laws through publicity
and education, as this is the reliable guarantee for law
observation and enforcement. "In China," he said, "the Party leads
the people in laying down the Constitution and laws, and it also
leads the people in observing and implementing them. Therefore the
Party must define its activities within the limits permitted by
the Constitution and laws."
</P>
<P>
Adhering to the Party's leadership, strictly abiding by laws in
handling affairs, and obeying to people's will are unified, he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0160 </DOCNO>
