<HEADLINE> DPRK: Japanese Shrine Visit Dangerous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The undisguised visit of Japanese
politicians to the "Yasukuni Shrine" shows the extent of danger
Japan's militarization has reached, the Rodong Sinmun newspaper of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) noted today in a
commentary.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper is referring to the April 22 visit by 223
Japanese dietmen including two ministers to the shrine, where
top-level Japanese war criminals are honored.
</P>
<P>
Having made full military preparations for overseas aggression,
the Japanese politicians are now working hard to lay ideological
and moral foundations for it, said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
They regard the visit to the shrine as an important lever in
their efforts to revive militarism, which becomes all the more
dangerous with the government encouragement, the commentary added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the paper said, the leaders of the Japanese
conservative parties are scheming to let foreigners visit the
shrine as a matter of duty during their tour of Japan, imbuing the
world people with Japanese militarist "outlook" and "philosophy,"
said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese politicians' visit to the shrine and efforts to
build Japan into a military power have invited the vigilance of
the neighboring countries that demand them to ponder over the
consequences, warned the commentary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
