<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 07:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Gloomy Prospect for Egyptian Textiles Industry (I) (by Hou Jia) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The prospect for the 7,000-year-old
Egyptian textile industry is gloomy as it has been cramped by
hikes of cotton price and lack of renovation.
</P>
<P>
Some even fear that the long-time industry is approaching the
verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The volume of textile exports, which represent about a quarter
of overall Egyptian exports, slumped by 21 percent to 2.5 billion
pounds (740 million U.S. dollars) in 1996 from 3 billion pounds
(880 million dollars) in 1995, according to a report by the
Committee of Industrial Production and Energy.
</P>
<P>
The limping industry is now fighting a losing war with its
fierce rivals in South Korea, Thailand, Taiwan, Turkey and
Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Egypt failed to compete with the top 10 textiles exporters
whose collective exports reached 95 billion dollars in 1994, or
73.8 percent of the world's total textile exports.
</P>
<P>
Nor is it made to the list of the biggest 10 clothes exporters,
which distributed 81.7 billion dollars worth of garments to the
world markets.
</P>
<P>
The industry, first initiated by the ancient Egyptians,
blossomed in 1927 after it was declared a nationally strategic
industry in Egypt. Its heyday came in 1949 when Egypt exported
textiles for the first time.
</P>
<P>
In fact, economists say it could have done a lot better given
the availability of high-quality cotton, the low-cost and skilled
labor if not for the rising prices of local cotton.
</P>
<P>
However, the cotton prices which soared 75 percent in the
past couple of years, have sent the cost higher and cramped the
operations of the public and private spinning factories alike.
</P>
<P>
Now, thousands of workers nationwide are waiting to pack up
after their textiles factories incurred appalling losses and banks
slammed the door in their face, refusing to float those sinking
ships.
</P>
<P>
According to Al Mousawar magazine, 31 public sector companies
have accumulated 1.2 billion dollars of losses, of which 400
million was reported last year alone.
</P>
<P>
The overdraft loans from bank also topped 4 billion while the
factories have to pay 250 million dollars in interest annually to
creditors.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the industry's woes, Moetz Billah Abdel Maqsoud,
Chairman of the Chamber of the Textiles, said that the industry
has been given a dazzling blow over the past three years when the
cotton price went wild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 07:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Gloomy Prospect for Egyptian Textiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Consequently, the production cost helplessly increased," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The same argument was upheld by Magdi al-Aref, director-general
of the Textile Industry Support Fund.
</P>
<P>
"The appalling rise in textiles production cost frightened
customers and persuaded them to seek cheaper products from India
and Pakistan late in the past two years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem of textiles industry in Egypt worsened when
textiles factories were forced to pay a minimum 10-12 percent
interest rate for the loans from banks to redress their course.
</P>
<P>
In one of the most endangered textiles factories, Qafr al-Dawar
Company for Weaving and Textiles that is also one of the largest
in the country, financial imbalance reached 26.5 million dollars
and overdrafts amounted to 140.3 million dollars, according to the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine also said the company's losses amounted to 102.9
million dollars, of which 85.3 million dollars were incurred under
its former board, which was later referred by the Public
Prosecution for investigation.
</P>
<P>
To avoid its imminent collapse, proposals include immediate
government intervention, bigger financial help, and partial sale
or rent of the factory and its facilities.
</P>
<P>
Looking back, Egypt's textiles industry used to find loyal
clients in the eastern European countries, which would import
Egyptian textile products for good prices, irrespective of
quality. Now, the situation is entirely different.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, only six Egyptian companies realized the threat
and made swift plans to modernize their equipment and machines,
while others were swiftly thrown out of the foreign market because
of the poor quality they offered, said Samir Ragab, Chairman of
Sinai Company.
</P>
<P>
The hard-hit companies were caught off guard as their managers
failed to raise investment funds to finance purchasing modern
machines, said Ragab.
</P>
<P>
The ordeal worsened when textiles stocks in their storehouses
were piling high while the workers' wages soared to more than 20
percent of the production cost.
</P>
<P>
The mess deterred banks from providing loans, and thus these
companies failed to raise fund to purchase cotton and make its
machines run again.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the vicious circle is broken, the industry can not
survive," Ragab lamented.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry, which is among Egypt's largest foreign
currency earners and a huge job-provider, is vital for the
country's industrial and economic structure, said the report of
the Committee of Industrial Production and Energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
