<HEADLINE> SADC, Malaysia to Hold Economic Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen African heads of
state are expected to hold an economic summit, due to open on
Saturday in northern Botswana, with Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad in a bid to boost bilateral cooperations.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's local daily the Citizen reported today that the
forthcoming five-day summit, jointly organized by the 12-member
Southern African Development Community (SADC) and Malaysia, is
intended to woo investors from all over the world to the
newly-opened economies of southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
President Ketumile Masire of Botswana, who is to co-host the
summit with Mahathir, told reporters on Thursday in Gaborone,
capital of Botswana, that participants hope to standardize
economic legislation in southern African countries to attract
investors to the region.
</P>
<P>
"The SADC countries still operate independently from each
other and we are working toward common legislation," said Masire.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the summit are the heads of state from the
SADC member states: Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Special guests to the summit include Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni and Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings. 
</P>
