<HEADLINE> India Regrets U.S. Move on Watch List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 2 (Xinhua) -- India has expressed regret at the
U.S. decision to continue to place it on a "priority watch list"
under the U.S. "Special 301" trade law provisions, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the decision, a spokesman of the Indian External
Affairs Ministry said Thursday that the move will not be in
consonance with the positive trend in the development of
commercial and business relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In a decision made on Wednesday, Washington placed India and a
number of other countries on the list for what it called their
failure to provide protection to American intellectual property,
particularly its patents.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the World Trade Organization, of which both
India and the United States are members, provides an appropriate
forum for discussion and resolution of these and other matters.
</P>
