<HEADLINE> Agassi Upset in Challenge Tennis Tournament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Andre Agassi joined the exodus of
seeds when he was forced out of the 328,000 US dollars AT&AMP;T
Challenge tennis tournament in Atlanta on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Fourth-seeded Agassi suffered a second-round loss to Magnus
Norman, ranked 81st, 7-6 (9-7) 3-6, 6-3, joining on the sidelines
with top-seeded Michael Chang, second seeded Jonas Bjorkman and
third seeded Jim Courier.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seeded Petr Korda of the Czech Republic survived a
three-set struggle with unseeded Johan Van Herck of Belgium,
winning 6-4, 1-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Seventh-seeded Jason Stoltenberg of Australia also advanced
with a 6-1, 7-5 victory over Spain's Juan Albert Viloca, and
Brazil's Fernando Meligeni beat Dennis van Scheppingen of the
Netherlands 6-3, 7-6 (7-1).
</P>
<P>
In a protracted baseline struggle, Norman missed his first
match point at 5-3 in the third set but kept cool to seal the
competition by winning his third match point.
</P>
<P>
In the first set, Agassi was challenged by the Swede from the
start and fought off six set points before it went to the
tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
Agassi left the court immediately after the loss. He had
suffered four consecutive first round losses this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
