<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Air Force Loses One More Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka Air Force (SLAF) has
lost one more aircraft, an Israeli-built unmanned air vehicle
(UAV), bringing the number of lost aircraft to 15 since the Tamil
rebels reneged on peace talks on April 19, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The UAV was flying over Omanthai in Vavuniya District Thursday
when it went missing. The SLAF has launched an operation to locate
it but there have still been no reports of sighting it yet,
informed sources here said.
</P>
<P>
This was the second aircraft lost after the SLAF got three of
them for surveillance purposes against the rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam who are fighting a 14-year
guerrilla war for a separate state in the north and east of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The first was lost while it was flying over Ponneryn in the
Jaffna Peninsula on January 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the 15 crashes so far, more than 250 security forces
personnel have been killed and the government has lost aircraft
worth 16.95 million U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
