<HEADLINE> Nepal Launches Programs to Improve Power Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has launched
new programs to make electricity services more effective and
simplified, officials here said.
</P>
<P>
New measures to make services like power connection, meter
reading, tariff collection and light fixing more prompt and
simplified have been arranged by the state-run Nepal Electricity
Authority, State Minister for Water Resources Rajib Parajui told a
press conference here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the state minister, the government has given top
priority to rural electrification with a view to raising the
quality of life of the people living in villages.
</P>
<P>
Under the on-going Seventh Power Project, electrification work
is under way in 22 districts of the country with the assistance of
the Asian Development Bank (ADB), the state minister said.
</P>
<P>
About 168,000 people in 900 villages are expected to benefit
from the project, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Nepal at present has a total
installed power generating capacity of 300 megawatts and some 85
percent of the country's 20 million people still have no access to
electricity.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Water Resources Ministry said at the press
conference that the government is in the process of studying the
possibility of implementing a couple of large-scale hydroelectric
projects with the involvement of private investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
