<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Workers' Health Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's rapid development over
the past few years has resulted in the degradation of the health
of workers and health problems are on the rise, according to
Deputy Public Health Minister Sora-At Klinprathum.
</P>
<P>
He said that as many as 6,712 factories in the country have
been categorized by the Occupational Health Division as "risky
areas" for the spread of silicosis, a lung disease caused by small
particles of dust.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by the division showed that at least 182,000
workers are at the risk of suffering from silicosis.
</P>
<P>
A random survey conducted of 2,600 workers in 80 industries
showed that 168 suffered from silicosis and most of them worked in
steel and quarry businesses.
</P>
<P>
The study also revealed that 14,440 industries, employing a
total of 558,000 workers, were high-risk areas for lead poisoning.
</P>
<P>
The number of workers suffering from blood poisoning caused by
metals and lung diseases caused by dust and petroleum are also on
the increase.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicated that the number of workers suffering from
petroleum poisoning increased from fewer than 20 cases in 1984 to
more than 70 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Pesticide poisoning among farmers also went up from 0.56
percent in 1972 to 6.91 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister urged industrialists to pay more attention
to the health of their employees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
