<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exporters Oppose Wage Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai exporters are opposed to a
minimum wage increase for workers this year as it will hurt them,
according to Viroj Amatakulchai, president of the Federation of
Thai Textile Industries.
</P>
<P>
He said exporters had received advance orders on the basis that
workers were being paid the current minimum wage of 157 baht
(about 6 U.S. dollars) a day.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government not to agree to the proposed 20-baht
(0.77 dollars) jump, as exporters are already struggling to boost
Thai products' competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Thailand's exports, a mainstay of the country's
economy, rose only 0.2 percent over the year before, as compared
with a projected 18-percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Labor unions have proposed the 20-baht increase for
consideration by a tripartite committee composed of
representatives of the government, employers and employees.
</P>
<P>
Viroj suggested that the minimum wage should remain in place
for at least two years before another rise is considered.
</P>
<P>
In the last few years, the minimum wage has been going up on an
annual basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
