<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Ready to Face Japan at WTO Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will probably face Japan's
second complaint to the panel of the World Trade Organization
(WTO) after the country rejected the suit, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Japan was reported to have officially forwarded a car dispute
to the WTO Dispute Settlement Board, complaining that Indonesia's
national car policy gives import and luxury tax exemptions to a
domestic car maker.
</P>
<P>
"I have heard that we have rejected Japan's proposal," Director
General for Foreign Economic Relations Sumadi Brotodiningrat said
here Thursday, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
It will take three weeks to one month for Japan to submit a
second claim to the WTO and Indonesia could not reject the second
claim, he said.
</P>
<P>
"During the grace period, we will prepare everything for such a
possibility," he said, adding that Indonesia will use
internationally reputable lawyers if the country has to face Japan
at the WTO panel.
</P>
<P>
Japan on Wednesday officially asked the WTO to form a panel to
arbitrate in a dispute over Indonesia's controversial national car
policy, trade sources said here.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the United States and the European Union have held a
series of bilateral talks with Indonesia after lodging a complaint
with the WTO in October last year in an attempt to get Jakarta to
remove measures which the three claim are discriminatory and
against multilateral trade rules.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government announced its national car policy in
February last year, under which domestic carmakers can enjoy tax
exemption on condition they raise the local content ratios in
their cars up to 60 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
The tax breaks were granted solely to Pt. Timor Putra Nasional,
a company controlled by President Soeharto's youngest son.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Eyes Myanmar Ports on Andaman Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is considering using a
Myanmar port on the Andaman Sea as an alternative route for Thai
goods being shipped to markets in Europe, according to Thai Deputy
Prime Minister and Industry Minister Korn Dabbaransi.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Industry Ministry is looking at two Myanmar ports --
Tavoy and Bokpyin -- and the Island of Kawtaung as part of a study
due for completion by the end of this year, Korn was quoted today
by local newspaper the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's choice will depend on economic viability and related
infrastructure requirements, he said.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar authorities have responded positively to the idea and
expressed "readiness" to develop the port which Thailand chose, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Korn will have further talks with his Myanmar counterpart later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 75 percent of Thailand's Europe-bound goods through
the Malacca Strait, shipping the goods through the Andaman Sea
would save time and cost.  
</P>
</TEXT>
