<HEADLINE> Kasparov Gears up for Rematch Against IBM Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian chess genius Garry Kasparov
will take the challenge from a smarter IBM computer for a rematch
scheduled to kick off in Manhattan on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The world chess champion, 34, said that "a computer will always
be beatable" because he can figure out its modus operandi and its
weaknesses after about 10 games against any computer.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Kasparov won the first faceoff by 4-2 against the
Deep Blue machine which was first developed by five computer
scientists and an American chess grandmaster in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the IBM team revamped the chip-stuffed IBM chess
whiz with a computer brain transplant that allows it to think
twice as fast as its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
Deep Blue scans 200 million moves per second, and examines 50
billion chess positions in the average three minutes allowed per
move by match rules.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov who will initiate the first game, may pocket in
700,000 US dollars should he eventually win the nine-day rematch
from the 64 black and white squares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
