<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeks Trade Liberalization Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand wants trade ministers of
the 18-member Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) to develop
rules in selecting which industrial sectors should be liberalized
first, according to a senior trade official.
</P>
<P>
Vitoon Tulyanonda, deputy director general of the Business
Economics Department of the Thai government was quoted by the
local press as saying the ministers must identify which sectors
should be liberalized before the 2010 deadline for developed
members and 2020 deadline for developing economies.
</P>
<P>
Trade ministers from APEC members are to meet in Montreal,
Canada, next week.
</P>
<P>
Thailand believed that clear criteria should be established to
create understanding among the members of the concepts and
approaches of early sectorial liberalization, he said.
</P>
<P>
The sectors should not duplicate those which have already been
determined by the World Trade Organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
APEC members should not only choose sectors that would yield
results but should also select those which would create a positive
impact on technology and economic cooperation, such as technology
transfer and human resource development.
</P>
<P>
Vitoon noted that some countries, like Australia, have proposed
early liberalization of the energy sector while others have sought
to open sectors such as textiles and agriculture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
