<HEADLINE> Indonesian Election Contestants Urged to Obey Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Central Committee for
the Election has sent a strong warning to three election
contestants against violation of campaign regulations, official
sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Singgih Sh. said in his office here Thursday
that he went to several regions and discovered the existence of
violations of the campaign regulations, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
"Until now, we have remained a little tolerant. But once
election contestants cross the line, we will not hesitate to
resort to legal action," Singgih was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three political parties -- the ruling party Golkar, the
United Development Party (PPP) and the Indonesian Democratic Party
(PDI) started their campaign on April 27 for the May 29 general
election. the campaign period will end on May 23.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that several incidents and traffic accidents
have occurred in Medan, North Sumatra, Yogyakarta, Central Java,
Ujung Pandand, South Sulawesi and some other cities since the
campaign began, killing more than 10 people and injuring dozens of
others.
</P>
<P>
The three parties all started their respective second rounds of
campaigning on Thursday. During the first round of campaigning,
the general situation was peaceful and stable, government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
In this year's campaign, the country is divided into three
groups of campaign areas where the three parties could conduct
their campaign activities in turns.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government also banned motor parades and marches
during the campaigning. However, some parties have violated the
rules by showing their strength in the streets.
</P>
<P>
The three parties are vying for 425 of the 500 seats of the
House of Representatives. The remaining 75 seats are reserved for
the Armed Forces whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
The country has nearly 124 million eligible voters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
