<HEADLINE> Kafelnikov Loses to Qualifier in Czech Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Yevgeny Kafelnikov joined the
exodus of seeds when he lost to qualifier Marcel Craca of Germany
in straight sets at the Czech Open tennis tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Kafelnikov who made a return from a three-month injury
layoff, became the fifth seed to lose in the first two rounds when
he was defeated 7-6 (7-4), 6-4 by Craca.
</P>
<P>
Craca, who ranked 135th on the ATP Tour, rallied from two games
down in both sets, advanced to the quarterfinals for the first
time this season.
</P>
<P>
Kafelnikov broke Craca early in the first set, but Craca
rallied to tie it 5-5 and went on to win the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
Craca was broken anew in the second set but again rattled the
Russian by winning four consecutive games from 1-3 down before
serving out the competition.
</P>
<P>
In other actions, second seed Marcelo Rios of Chile advanced
easily by beating Stephane Simian of France 6-4, 6-2, Emilio
Alvarez of Spain beat countryman Carlos Costa 7-5, 6-4, 4-6, and
Fabrice Santoro of France defeated Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil 7-6
(7-4), 3-6, 6-1. 
</P>
