<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. to Start Talks on Anti-drug Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Panama and the United States
will start formal negotiations on June 1 to establish a
multinational anti-drug center at the Howard U.S. Air Force Base
in the Panama Canal, a Panamanian official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Eduardo Ritter, president of the Transition Commission on
the Panama Canal, told the press that preparations for the formal
negotiations will be finished in the last days of May.
</P>
<P>
Ritter, who is representing Panama in the contacts with
U.S. ambassador John Negroponte on the matter, said the two
countries will appoint their negotiating teams in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have reached agreement in principle on most
of the issues discussed, which Ritter did not specify.
</P>
<P>
The main dispute is the number of U.S. troops to be deployed in
the anti-drug center. Panama prefers a reduction, while the United
States wants to deploy more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also wants to retain its communications facilities on
the Galeta Island and two buildings in Corozal, Panama City, from
which classified military information is transmitted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
