<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (57-58) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 2 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (57-58) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: What are the characteristics of Hong Kong as a free
port?
</P>
<P>
Answer: A free port refers to an economic area that is
completely open to the outside and free for entry and exit,
including the freedom to establish enterprises, free trade, free
shipping, free exchange of currencies and the free flow of capital
and personnel.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been a free port for more than 150 years. In
comparison with other free ports around the world, Hong Kong has
the following characteristics:
</P>
<P>
1. Fairly big in area. Hong Kong is a free port city covering
the Hong Kong Island, Kowloon and the "New Territories." Other
free ports are confined to a small section of a particular city or
area such as the Hamburg free port and the Rotterdam free port.
</P>
<P>
2. A high degree of opening. Hong Kong allows a free flow of
all kinds of capital, which can be invested in all industries and
business lines.
</P>
<P>
3. All-encompassing in functions. Hong Kong has a comprehensive
economic structure in which trade, financial, shipping, real
estate, manufacturing, retail, tourist, and information industries
are all highly developed. Other free ports tend to focus on one
particular industry such as processing, transfer trade, offshore
banking or tourism.
</P>
<P>
4. Big economic strength. Despite having only a population of 6
million living in an area of 1,000 square km, Hong Kong is a
well-established center of international economic activities.
</P>
<P>
With the enactment of the Basic Law, factors contributing to
the economic success of Hong Kong as a free port has been
enshrined in law. This will ensure that Hong Kong continue to
enjoy its unique superiorities.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will the status of Hong Kong as an international
shipping center change after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Absolutely not. The reason are as follows:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, Hong Kong's status as an international shipping center
has resulted from a combination of factors, including advantageous
geographical location, a good sea port, a vast economic hinterland
(that is, the mainland), and extensive international economic
relations. These factors will not change after the transfer of
government there in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, according to the Basic Law, Hong Kong will maintain
its status as a free port and retain its free trade system after
1997. The Hong Kong SAR will participate in relevant international
organizations and international trade agreements such as the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (now the World Trade
Organization) as a separate customs territory. Its trade with the
rest of the world will further develop, and this in turn will
promote the development of its shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, the Hong Kong SAR will maintain its previous systems
of shipping management and shipping regulation. With authorization
from the central government, the Hong Kong SAR may handle ship
registering, allow foreign ships to enter and leave its port in
accordance with law except foreign warships, and permit private
shipping and the free operation of shipping-related businesses and
private container terminals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970502.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-02 </DATE_TIME>
