<HEADLINE> Clashes Mar May Day Celebrations in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 1 (Xinhua) -- Violent clashes involving neo-Nazis
marred the International Labor Day celebrations today in Germany.
</P>
<P>
In the western German state of Lower Saxony, about 300
neo-Nazis clashed with about 50 left-wing extremists in the town
of Hannoversch Muenden. Some 40 neo-Nazis were detained and one
police officer was injured, police said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 4,500 policemen were deployed in the eastern
state of Saxony to prevent neo-Nazis from reaching the city of
Leipzig and disrupting the traditional May Day trade union rally
which was attended by an estimated 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Police said they had taken some 150 rightists, mostly young
males, into temporary custody in and around Leipzig.
</P>
<P>
At one point in Leipzig, about 150 left-wingers hurled rocks
and fireworks at police, who were trying to keep them apart from a
small group of skinheads.
</P>
<P>
Police also prevented right extremists from holding marches in
the nearby town of Halle, and in Aschaffenburg and Alsfeld in the
state of Hesse.
</P>
<P>
In Dortmund, police took 46 supporters of the rightist National
Democratic Party of Germany into temporary custody and seized from
them a number of unconstitutional propaganda materials.
</P>
<P>
In the German capital of Berlin, violence broke out at two May
Day demonstrations. Bottles, stones and fireworks were hurled at
police from a crowd of 6,500 left-wingers in central Berlin.
Police responded with water cannon and detained about 70
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the German Trade Union Federation (DGB) Dieter
Schulte warned at a mass rally in Hamburg that a social explosion
could only be avoided by a sharp reduction in mass unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in Leipzig, leader of Germany's largest trade union
IG Metall, Klaus Zwickel, accused the Bonn government of doing
nothing against the record unemployment in Germany which currently
stands at about 4.5 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
