<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls on Softer Economic Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell here today
after touching a new 4-year high against the yen.
</P>
<P>
Based on the new economic data, foreign exchange traders
reasoned that the likelihood the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates at its May 20 meeting has decreased. The prospect
of rising rates has been a major force helping to push the dollar
higher.
</P>
<P>
The dollar hit an intraday high of 127.47 yen, the strongest
since August 1992, before retreating to settle in New York at
126.51 yen, down from 127.06 yen Wednesday. The dollar cost 1.7217
marks, down from 1.7303.
</P>
<P>
There was little movement in the pound ahead of the conclusion
of the British elections. Sterling strengthened slightly to 1.6242
U.S. dollars from 1.6237 U.S. dollars Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday:
5.8050 French francs, down from 5.8300; 1.4695 Swiss francs, down
from 1.4728; 1,703.00 Italian lire, down from 1,710.00; 1.3872
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3963. 
