<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Edge Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 1 (Xinhua) -- The technology sector of the New
York Stock Exchange advanced for the fourth straight session, but
blue-chip shares suffered some profit-taking today.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 32.51 points to 6,976.48.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-8 margin,
with the volume totaling 459.34 million shares, down from 556.07
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader measures were mixed, with money moving from the
blue-chip sector to technology issues and other areas that haven't
recovered as fully from the market recent slide.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 2.81 to 798.53, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 1.23 to 415.71.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 9.74 to 1,270.50, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.59 to 558.50.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Friday's report on the April wage levels, investors
moved to secure some gains from a three-day rally that added 270
points to the Dow and boosted it above 7,000 for the first time
since mid-March, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Investors are concerned that without some sign of moderation,
the central bank will raise rates repeatedly, potentially choking
company profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
